"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759423","Northern Ireland Office","false","2017-09-15","<p>My Department has not received any services from the Behavioural Insights Team since 2014.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p>","Norwich North","Chloe Smith",,"2017-09-15T10:20:14.667Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759423/answer","Biography information for Chloe Smith","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759423/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759423/answer",,,,,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2017-09-11","Northern Ireland Office: Behavioural Insights Team","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, what services his Department has received from the Behavioural Insights Team since 2014.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","9971"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759424","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-09-19","<p>Due to diary commitments the Minister for Sport and Civil Society (with responsibility for youth policy) was unable to attend the 9th Commonwealth Youth Ministers meeting from 31<sup>st</sup> July to 4<sup>th</sup> August in Uganda. Officials from the Cabinet Office Commonwealth Team and the Department for International Development were in attendance. Subject to diary commitments a Minister will attend the next meeting in Jamaica in 2021.</p><p><strong><br> </strong></p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2017-09-19T10:01:23.003Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759424/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759424/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759424/answer",,,,,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-09-11","Commonwealth: Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, for what reasons the Government did not sent a Minister to the 9th Commonwealth Youth Ministers meeting in Uganda to prepare for hosting the Commonwealth Heads of Government Meeting in 2018; and if the Government will commit to sending a Minister to the 10th Commonwealth Youth Ministers meeting in Jamaica in 2021.","false","Biography information for Cat Smith","Lancaster and Fleetwood","Cat Smith","9737"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759425","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-09-19","<p>​The UK is not currently on the new Commonwealth Youth Ministerial Task Force. The Task Force is made up of 10 members representing the Commonwealth's regions; this includes Malta as the representative for Europe.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2017-09-19T09:33:46.287Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759425/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759425/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759425/answer",,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-09-11","Commonwealth: Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, whether the Government was appointed as a member of the new Commonwealth Youth Ministerial Task Force following the 9th Commonwealth Youth Minister meeting in Uganda, as outlined in point 20 of the Final Communiqué.","false","Biography information for Cat Smith","Lancaster and Fleetwood","Cat Smith","9738"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759426","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-09-19","<p>In April 2018, the UK will host the Commonwealth Heads of Government Meeting in London and Windsor. The summit will involve three days of forums and the two day Heads of Government Meeting. The Commonwealth Youth Forum is a key part of this, providing an opportunity for the young people of the Commonwealth to debate the challenges they face and develop proposals that will be put to decision makers, ensuring they have a voice in the Commonwealth's future.</p><p>The agenda for the Commonwealth Youth Forum is developed by an International Taskforce, made up of young leaders from across the Commonwealth and the UK as Host country, working in partnership with the Commonwealth Youth Council.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2017-09-19T09:57:33.117Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759426/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759426/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759426/answer",,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-09-11","Commonwealth Heads of Government Meeting: Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what steps the Government is taking to ensure that young people are represented at the Commonwealth Heads of Government meeting in 2018.","false","Biography information for Cat Smith","Lancaster and Fleetwood","Cat Smith","9739"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759427","Scotland Office","false","2017-09-13","<p>The Scotland Office has not received services from the Behavioural Insights Team.</p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell",,"2017-09-13T10:19:33.443Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759427/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759427/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759427/answer",,,,,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2017-09-11","Scotland Office: Behavioural Insights Team","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, what services his Department has received from the Behavioural Insights Team since 2014.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","9972"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759428","Department for Transport","false","2017-09-19","<p>The Department for Transport has received services from the Behavioural Insights Team since 2014. This has enabled the department to add to its evidence base to support priority government areas.</p><p> </p><p>Since January 2011, details of central government contracts above the value of £10,000 are published on Contracts Finder. Contracts published prior to 26 February 2015 can be viewed at:</p><p><a href="https://data.gov.uk/data/contracts-finder-archive" target="_blank">https://data.gov.uk/data/contracts-finder-archive</a></p><p> </p><p>Those published after 26 February 2015 can be viewed at: <a href="https://www.contractsfinder.service.gov.uk/Search" target="_blank">https://www.contractsfinder.service.gov.uk/Search</a></p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2017-09-19T10:01:03.507Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759428/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759428/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759428/answer",,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-09-11","Department for Transport: Behavioural Insights Team","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what services his Department has received from the Behavioural Insights Team since 2014.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","9973"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759429","Department for Transport","false","2017-09-19","<p>We are committed to improving safety for all vulnerable road users. We will continue to deliver safety advice to motorcyclists, cyclists, motorists and pedestrians through the THINK! and THINK BIKER social media channels, and work with partners to develop cycling/motorcycling campaign messages that raise awareness of specific dangers, including those mentioned.</p><p> </p><p>The purpose of THINK! is to reduce the number of people killed and seriously injured on our roads. Campaign priorities are determined on this basis. They are thoroughly researched and evidenced using casualty data, road safety literature and audience insight.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-09-19T09:46:48.967Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759429/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759429/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759429/answer",,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-09-11","Cycling: Safety","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if he will include, as part of the Think public information campaign on road safety, messages which highlights the risks of harm to cyclists and motorbike riders when people open car doors without looking to see who is coming up behind them.","false","Biography information for Theresa Villiers","Chipping Barnet","Theresa Villiers","9877"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759430","Department for Transport","false","2017-09-18","<p>I refer to my previous answer to the honourable member dated 11 September that the Department has had Board level discussions with Transport Scotland about improving the remainder of the A1 from Newcastle to Scotland, and will continue to look at the case for completing the dualling of the route, taking into account Scotland’s revised Transport Strategy upon its publication. Improvements to the A1 in Scotland are the responsibility of the devolved administration, but Highways England will consider the effects that improvements in Scotland may have on the A1 in England.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-09-18T08:31:36.277Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759430/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759430/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759430/answer",,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-09-11","A1: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what discussions he has had with the Scottish Government on road improvements to the A1 in Scotland and the effect on that part of the road of improvements to the A1 from Newcastle to the Scottish border.","false","Biography information for John Lamont","Berwickshire, Roxburgh and Selkirk","John Lamont","9895"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759431","Department for Transport","false","2017-09-14","<p>Agreement in principle was reached with the Welsh Government last year that they would be given a combination of statutory executive franchising functions within Wales, and agency powers of the Secretary of State in relation to the English component of the franchise, in order that that they could procure and manage a new franchise of similar geographic scope, while ensuring the Secretary of State’s accountability for rail operations within England.</p><p>In order to facilitate the timely progression of the Welsh Government’s procurement, the Secretary of State entered into the first of a planned series of agency agreements with Welsh Ministers in October last year. Each agreement will set out relevant conditions to protect the Secretary of State’s interests in the English component of the franchise (including the English component of cross-border services). The Government also continues to progress the transfer of functions Order to give effect to the transfer to Welsh Ministers of executive franchising functions in Wales.</p><p>The Department is actively and constructively engaging with Welsh Government to both protect the Secretary of State’s interests and enable them to achieve a successful procurement of the next Wales &amp; Borders franchise from October 2018.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard","9749","2017-09-14T13:19:32.057Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759431/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759431/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759431/answer",,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-09-11","Wales and Borders Rail Franchise","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what powers the Welsh Government and Transport for Wales have in the design, content, tendering and award of the next Wales and Borders and Metro franchise.","false","Biography information for Jo Stevens","Cardiff Central","Jo Stevens","9745"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759432","Department for Transport","false","2017-09-14","<p>The Welsh Government has been working closely with Network Rail to agree the principles for the proposed transfer of ownership of the Valley Lines. Such transfer is supported in principle by the government, subject to final agreement and recommendation of approval by Network Rail.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2017-09-14T13:14:39.953Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759432/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759432/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759432/answer",,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-09-11","Valley Lines","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether an agreement has been reached on the proposed transfer of ownership of the Valley Lines to the Welsh Government.","false","Biography information for Jo Stevens","Cardiff Central","Jo Stevens","9746"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759433","Department for Transport","false","2017-09-14","<p>The Office of Rail and Road is the statutory economic and safety regulator for the rail industry in Great Britain. In relation to the proposed transfer of ownership of the Valley Lines, its role will be to ensure that the transfer does not prejudice the interests of other rail industry parties and that the subsequent operator of the Valley Lines infrastructure has in place all necessary licences and other authorisations to ensure that operates in a safe and efficient manner, in the public interest.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2017-09-14T13:21:52.453Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759433/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759433/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759433/answer",,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-09-11","Valley Lines","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what the role is of the Office of Rail and Road in any proposed transfer of ownership of the Valley Lines to the Welsh Government.","false","Biography information for Jo Stevens","Cardiff Central","Jo Stevens","9747"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759434","Department for Transport","false","2017-09-14","<p>Network Rail has been considering carefully the risks associated with the proposed transfer of ownership of the Valley Lines. Both it and the Welsh Government have been developing an agreement based upon Network Rail being held harmless for the direct impacts upon its business of the proposed transfer.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2017-09-14T13:24:39.517Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759434/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759434/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759434/answer",,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-09-11","Valley Lines","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what assessment has been made of the risk associated with the proposed transfer of ownership of the Valley Lines to the Welsh Government.","false","Biography information for Jo Stevens","Cardiff Central","Jo Stevens","9748"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759435","Department for Transport","false","2017-09-14","<p>Agreement in principle was reached with the Welsh Government last year that they would be given a combination of statutory executive franchising functions within Wales, and agency powers of the Secretary of State in relation to the English component of the franchise, in order that that they could procure and manage a new franchise of similar geographic scope, while ensuring the Secretary of State’s accountability for rail operations within England.</p><p>In order to facilitate the timely progression of the Welsh Government’s procurement, the Secretary of State entered into the first of a planned series of agency agreements with Welsh Ministers in October last year. Each agreement will set out relevant conditions to protect the Secretary of State’s interests in the English component of the franchise (including the English component of cross-border services). The Government also continues to progress the transfer of functions Order to give effect to the transfer to Welsh Ministers of executive franchising functions in Wales.</p><p>The Department is actively and constructively engaging with Welsh Government to both protect the Secretary of State’s interests and enable them to achieve a successful procurement of the next Wales &amp; Borders franchise from October 2018.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard","9745","2017-09-14T13:19:32.103Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759435/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759435/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759435/answer",,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-09-11","Wales and Borders Rail Franchise","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what powers his Department has in the design, content, tendering and award of the next Wales and Borders and Metro franchise.","false","Biography information for Jo Stevens","Cardiff Central","Jo Stevens","9749"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759436","Department for Transport","false","2017-09-14","<p>The Driver and Vehicle Standards Agency (DVSA) includes “Checking for oncoming cyclists, pedestrians and other traffic before opening the car door” as part of its National Standards for driving.</p><p> </p><p>In addition, DVSA covers the safe method of opening car doors in the Instructional Ability element of its Approved Driving Instructor (ADI) qualification process. This ensures that ADIs teach this method to novice drivers.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-09-14T10:05:16.65Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759436/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759436/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759436/answer",,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-09-11","Driving Tests","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if he will make it his policy to reform the driving test to highlight the risks of harm to cyclists and motorbike riders of people opening car doors without looking to see who is approaching from behind.","false","Biography information for Theresa Villiers","Chipping Barnet","Theresa Villiers","9754"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759437","Department for Transport","false","2017-09-14","<p>Once released by South Western railway, the trains will be returned to their owner (Angel Trains Ltd) who will be responsible for finding a future operator to lease the trains.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2017-09-14T10:09:33.46Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759437/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759437/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759437/answer",,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-09-11","Rolling Stock","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what plans his Department has for the future use of Class 707 trains which South Western Railway plan to stop using in 2019.","false","Biography information for Peter Kyle","Hove","Peter Kyle","9752"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759438","Department for Transport","false","2017-09-18","<p>The Departments for Transport, Work and Pensions and Education are working with stakeholders to address this issue. This includes the development of a new Trailblazer Apprenticeship standard for HGV drivers funded through the Apprenticeship Levy, help for jobseekers to enter the logistics sector and work to address the gender imbalance in the industry.</p><p> </p><p>As part of efforts to improve the image of the profession the Department for Transport has also commissioned a survey of roadside facilities and is working with Highways England, local authorities and operators to ensure more and better quality facilities for drivers.</p><p> </p><p>The Department and its agencies have also worked to minimise delays in obtaining an HGV test appointments and licence renewals.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-09-18T08:35:58.447Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759438/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759438/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759438/answer",,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-09-11","Large Goods Vehicle Drivers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what assessment he has made of the reasons for the shortage of qualified HGV drivers in the road haulage industry; what steps he is taking to address that shortage; and if he will make a statement.","true","Biography information for Charlie Elphicke","Dover","Charlie Elphicke","9700"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759439","Department for Transport","false","2017-09-19","<p>The Civil Aviation Authority (CAA) has been designated by the Secretary of State for Transport as the National Enforcement Body (NEB) for Regulation (EC) 261/2004 regarding compensation, and assistance to passengers in the event of denied boarding, and of cancellation and long delay of flights. The CAA offers advice to passengers and is able to take enforcement action against airlines that are not fulfilling their obligations.</p><p> </p><p>In addition, the Government and the CAA, have introduced an Alternative Dispute Resolution (ADR) scheme into the sector, which now covers more than 70% of passengers.</p><p> </p><p>The provision of ADR services for consumer disputes stemming from contracts for aviation services is designed to benefit consumers and lead to quick, fair, low cost (if not free) and binding solutions to their problems. ADR means passengers can settle disputes without asking a court to decide on the issue.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-09-19T15:39:22.75Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759439/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759439/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759439/answer",,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-09-11","Aviation: Compensation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what steps he is taking to ensure that air passengers can effectively and easily access compensation for long flight delays under EU Regulation 261/2004.","false","Biography information for Stuart C. McDonald","Cumbernauld, Kilsyth and Kirkintilloch East","Stuart C. McDonald","9729"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759440","Department for Transport","false","2017-09-19","<p>The Department for Transport and HM Treasury officials continue to work with Nexus regarding their proposals for new rolling stock on the Metro.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-09-19T09:57:08.633Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759440/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759440/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759440/answer",,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-09-11","Tyne and Wear Metro: Rolling Stock","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, when he plans to announce a decision on the delivery of a new train fleet for the Tyne and Wear Metro.","false","Biography information for Julie Elliott","Sunderland Central","Julie Elliott","9733"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759441","Department for Transport","false","2017-09-19","<p>The Department for Transport is currently in discussions with Nexus about funding options for the renewal of the Metro fleet. These discussions include consideration of revenue and capital support for the existing network beyond the current funding arrangement.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-09-19T09:54:43.05Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759441/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759441/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759441/answer",,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-09-11","Tyne and Wear Metro: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what his Department's plans are for funding of the Tyne and Wear Metro after the current funding arrangement ends in 2021.","false","Biography information for Julie Elliott","Sunderland Central","Julie Elliott","9734"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759442","Department for Transport","false","2017-09-18","<p>The Driver and Vehicle Standards Agency issues fines, known as ‘fixed penalties’, for breaches of cabotage and combined transport rules.</p><p> </p><p>The number of fixed penalties <em>issued</em> for breaches of cabotage and combined transport rules in each of the last five years is:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Year</p></td><td><p>Number of fines (fixed penalties) issued</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012</p></td><td><p>235</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013</p></td><td><p>281</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014</p></td><td><p>299</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015</p></td><td><p>517</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016</p></td><td><p>313</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>A cabotage offence is against the operator of a vehicle, not the driver, and can only be issued to non-GB operators.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p>The number of fixed penalties <em>paid</em> for breaches of cabotage and combined transport rules in each of the last five years is:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Year</p></td><td><p>Number of fines (fixed penalties) paid</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012</p></td><td><p>154</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013</p></td><td><p>125</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014</p></td><td><p>151</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015</p></td><td><p>273</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016</p></td><td><p>162</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p><strong> </strong></p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-09-18T08:43:43.147Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759442/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759442/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759442/answer",,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-09-11","Cabotage: Fines","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many fines have been (a) issued and (b) paid for breaches of cabotage and combined transport rules in each of the last five years for which data is available.","false","Biography information for Charlie Elphicke","Dover","Charlie Elphicke","9703"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759443","Department for Transport","false","2017-09-19","<p>It is local authorities who are responsible for enforcing the requirements of the Environmental Protection Act 1990 and section 122 of the Railways Act 1993.</p><p> </p><p>The ORR as the regulator of the rail industry is responsible for ensuring that engineering work is carried appropriately and those undertaking these tasks have adequate systems and procedures to ensure compliance with these Acts.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2017-09-19T13:44:47.967Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759443/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759443/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759443/answer",,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-09-11","Railways: Repairs and Maintenance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what guidance his Department provides to local authorities on their powers to take noise abatement enforcement against companies undertaking engineering work on the railways with respect to the Environmental Protection Act 1990 and section 122 of the Railways Act 1993.","false","Biography information for Jack Lopresti","Filton and Bradley Stoke","Jack Lopresti","9704"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759444","Department for Transport","false","2017-09-14","<p>The Freedom Pass is managed by London Councils and the policy on who is entitled to hold one is a matter for the Mayor. The Department does not hold statistics on how many Freedom Pass holders there are.</p><p> </p><p>Rail passenger journeys to/from and within London are published by Office of</p><p> </p><p>Rail and Road here:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://dataportal.orr.gov.uk/displayreport/report/html/4277ce6b-bdf3-4562-a6b1-eb036b57f065" target="_blank">https://dataportal.orr.gov.uk/displayreport/report/html/4277ce6b-bdf3-4562-a6b1-eb036b57f065</a></p><p> </p><p>The total number of passenger journeys (within London and to and from London) in thousands in the last five years available is as follows:</p><p> </p><p>2015/2016: 934,588</p><p>2014/2015: 878,042</p><p>2013/2014: 834,528</p><p>2012/2013: 787,471</p><p>2011/2012: 752,226</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-09-14T10:01:23.037Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759444/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759444/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759444/answer",,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-09-11","Travel: Greater London","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many people who hold a disabled person's freedom pass live in London; how many people who hold an older person's freedom pass live in London; and how many rail passengers there were in London in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Ms Harriet Harman","Camberwell and Peckham","Ms Harriet Harman","9825"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759445","Department for Transport","false","2017-09-14","<p>The Department for Transport has recently published its High Level Output Specification (HLOS) for rail which sets out demand forecasts for years 2018/19 and 2023/24.</p><p> </p><p>These forecasts are published at Table 2 of Annex A, which could be found at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/630675/high-level-output-specification-print.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/630675/high-level-output-specification-print.pdf</a></p><p> </p><p>These forecasts are for peak hour and peak 3 hour demand on all South West Trains services into Waterloo. For the peak three hours, the arrivals into Waterloo are 119,100 and rises to 123,500 by 2023/24. That is why we are currently investing in the Waterloo and South West upgrade programme, which will provide space for 30 per cent more passengers during the busiest times of the day.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Government recognises the case for further capacity improvements in London and the South East, such as those that Crossrail 2 could deliver. We are currently considering TfL’s business case for the proposal, which contains analysis of the impact Crossrail 2 could have on crowding across London and the South East.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2017-09-14T13:30:05.033Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759445/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759445/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759445/answer",,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-09-11","Railways: Passengers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, with reference to his Department's paper, Rail passenger numbers and crowding statistics: 2016 report, published on 27 July 2017, what assessment his Department has made of (a) future crowding on South West Mainline into Waterloo and (b) the effect of Crossrail 2 on those figures.","false","Biography information for Sir Vince Cable","Twickenham","Sir Vince Cable","9773"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759446","Department for Transport","false","2017-09-19","<p>On 25 October 2016, this Government announced that a Northwest Runaway at Heathrow Airport, combined with a package of supporting measures, was its preferred scheme to deliver additional airport capacity in the South East of England. The supporting measures would include improved rail access to the airport and we are actively looking at what we could do to accelerate these.</p><p> </p><p>The next step for the proposed Southern Rail Access is a GRIP 1-2 study to permit informed option appraisal. This is being considered alongside the detailed development of Western Rail Access plans for the airport, in order to ensure that we provide maximum benefit for airport and non-airport passengers and exploit the new journey opportunities this may provide.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2017-09-19T13:40:33.647Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759446/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759446/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759446/answer",,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-09-11","Heathrow Airport: Railways","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what progress has been made on bringing forward a new southern rail access link to Heathrow Airport.","false","Biography information for Jim Fitzpatrick","Poplar and Limehouse","Jim Fitzpatrick","9794"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759447","Wales Office","false","2017-09-15","<p>The Wales Office has neither received services from, nor paid money to, the Behavioural Insights Team since 2014.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Aberconwy","Guto Bebb","9687","2017-09-15T10:33:04.907Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759447/answer","Biography information for Guto Bebb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759447/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759447/answer",,,,,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2017-09-11","Wales Office: Behavioural Insights Team","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, what services his Department has received from the Behavioural Insights Team since 2014.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","9974"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759448","Women and Equalities","false","2017-09-14","<p>The Government Equalities Office has contracted the Behavioural Improvement Team (BIT) to carry out research over the period from January 2017 until July 2018 into parental decision-making concerning the sharing of childcare responsibilities and return to work. As part of this project, the BIT is also designing interventions to test which factors encourage parents to equalise the gender balance of work and childcare responsibilities.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-09-14T08:10:38.807Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759448/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759448/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759448/answer",,,,,,,,"31","Women and Equalities","Women and Equalities","2017-09-11","Government Equalities Office: Behavioural Insights Team","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for Women and Equalities, what services the Government Equalities Office has received from the Behavioural Insights Team since 2014.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","9966"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759449","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-14","<p>This change will come into effect in autumn 2017 and will apply to those with the most severe health conditions and disabilities who are placed in Employment and Support Allowance’s Support Group and the Universal Credit equivalent.</p><p> </p><p>We are working with stakeholders to finalise the criteria, once completed, the amended guidance will be incorporated into the Work Capability Assessment Handbook published annually on GOV.UK. This change will be reflected in the summer 2018 update.</p><p> </p><p>Through the development of the criteria we have consulted with a range of organisations, including representatives from some of the major health and disability charities through a stakeholder representative group.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt","9977","2017-09-14T17:00:11.443Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759449/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759449/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759449/answer",,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-11","Employment and Support Allowance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, when he plans to publish the criteria for exemption from employment and support allowance reassessments for people with long-term health conditions.","false","Biography information for Debbie Abrahams","Oldham East and Saddleworth","Debbie Abrahams","9976"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759450","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-14","<p>This change will come into effect in autumn 2017 and will apply to those with the most severe health conditions and disabilities who are placed in Employment and Support Allowance’s Support Group and the Universal Credit equivalent.</p><p> </p><p>We are working with stakeholders to finalise the criteria, once completed, the amended guidance will be incorporated into the Work Capability Assessment Handbook published annually on GOV.UK. This change will be reflected in the summer 2018 update.</p><p> </p><p>Through the development of the criteria we have consulted with a range of organisations, including representatives from some of the major health and disability charities through a stakeholder representative group.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt","9976","2017-09-14T17:00:11.38Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759450/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759450/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759450/answer",,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-11","Employment and Support Allowance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, which organisations his Department consulted when drawing up the criteria for exemption from employment and support allowance reassessments for people with long-term health conditions.","false","Biography information for Debbie Abrahams","Oldham East and Saddleworth","Debbie Abrahams","9977"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759451","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-18","<p>Training for Health Professionals on how to identify the impact of mental health conditions on a claimant’s ability to carry out the activities in either assessment, is already a key feature of the training programmes provided by the Assessment Providers.</p><p> </p><p>All Assessment Providers frequently engage with medical experts, charities and relevant stakeholders including mental-health organisations, to strengthen, review and update training programmes for all their Health Professionals.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2017-09-18T15:35:15.337Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759451/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759451/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759451/answer",,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-11","Social Security Benefits","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, whether he has plans to increase mental health training for personal independent payment and employment and support allowance assessors.","false","Biography information for Debbie Abrahams","Oldham East and Saddleworth","Debbie Abrahams","9943"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759452","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-18","<p>The information requested is not collated centrally and could only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2017-09-18T13:23:10.477Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759452/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759452/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759452/answer",,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-11","Department for Work and Pensions: Behavioural Insights Team","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what services his Department has received from the Behavioural Insights Team since 2014.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","9975"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759453","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-14","<p>Currently DWP does not have plans to change its policy on exemptions from conditionality and sanctions, for those people in the Employment and Support Allowance Support Group.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2017-09-14T13:49:53.567Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759453/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759453/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759453/answer",,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-11","Employment and Support Allowance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, if he will make it his policy to maintain the exemptions from conditionality and sanctions accorded to people in the employment and support allowance support group.","false","Biography information for Debbie Abrahams","Oldham East and Saddleworth","Debbie Abrahams","9986"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759454","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-14","<p>Improving Lives; the Work, Health and Disability Green Paper was published on 31 October 2016 and the consultation closed on 17 February 2017. The Green Paper explored a range of ways to improve the prospects and transform the lives of disabled people by removing barriers that prevent them from working, and helping ensure that they are able to remain in employment. We received around 6000 responses and engaged in a wide range of conversations with stakeholders during the consultation period. We are now carefully considering the consultation responses and next steps for longer-term reform and will set these out in the autumn.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2017-09-14T13:55:50.927Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759454/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759454/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759454/answer",,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-11","Employment: Disability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, when his Department plans to respond to the responses to his Department's consultation entitled, Work, Health and Disability: Improving Lives; and whether he plans to publish a White Paper on that subject.","false","Biography information for Debbie Abrahams","Oldham East and Saddleworth","Debbie Abrahams","9987"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759455","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-14","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the answer I gave on 25 July 2017 to <a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Commons/2017-07-17/5325/" target="_blank">Question UIN 5325</a>.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2017-09-14T13:47:00.263Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759455/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759455/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759455/answer",,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-11","Personal Independence Payment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what assessment he has made of the potential merits of exempting people with long-term progressive health conditions who are in receipt of the higher rate care and mobility personal independence payment components, from reassessment for that payment.","false","Biography information for Debbie Abrahams","Oldham East and Saddleworth","Debbie Abrahams","9988"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759456","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-14","<p>The assessment for Personal Independence Payment (PIP) is designed to treat people as individuals, considering the impact of their impairment or health condition on their everyday life and how each claimant has personally adapted to living with a disability, whether or not medication is prescribed or used. The PIP assessment is not a medical assessment, requiring the Health Professional to diagnose a condition or its severity and recommend treatment options; instead it focuses on the claimant’s functional ability.</p><p>There is no automatic entitlement to PIP by virtue of a health condition (except in terminal illness cases), either for new claimants or those claimants who were in receipt of Disability Living Allowance and who are being reassessed under PIP.</p><p>The PIP Assessment Guide for Health Professionals includes guidance on the assessment criteria and how they should be applied. This guidance can be accessed on the gov.uk website:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/547146/pip-assessment-guide.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/547146/pip-assessment-guide.pdf</a></p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2017-09-14T13:52:59.38Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759456/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759456/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759456/answer",,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-11","Personal Independence Payment: Medical Examinations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, if he will ensure that personal independence payments claimants who suffer from a condition for which there is not yet any medication are not disadvantaged by that fact in their assessments.","false","Biography information for Martyn Day","Linlithgow and East Falkirk","Martyn Day","9804"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759457","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-14","<p>The data requested is not available.</p><p><br>Access to Work support for travel to work is dependent on whether an individual has an inability to use public transport to travel to work, not whether they are in receipt of PIP. Therefore, this information is not collected.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2017-09-14T16:40:57.723Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759457/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759457/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759457/answer",,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-11","Access to Work Programme: Taxis","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many personal independence payment claimants who no longer receive mobility payment are having taxis paid for under the Access to Work scheme; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Martyn Day","Linlithgow and East Falkirk","Martyn Day","9805"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759458","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-15","<p>Trustees and providers of defined contribution (DC) pension schemes are required to issue annual statements to members which must include the current value of the pension pot, the amount contributed in the previous year and a projected estimate of what pension income the pot may buy at retirement. We have no plans to require employers to issue such statements.</p><p> </p><p>Employers who sponsor defined benefit (DB) pension schemes are not required to issue annual pension statements, although some sponsors do. However if a statement is requested by a member sponsors of DB schemes are required to issue one within two months.</p><p> </p><p>As defined benefit (DB) pensions normally promise a specific income in relation to salary and length of service, there are minimal annual fluctuations in entitlement. Placing a legal requirement on DB schemes to issue annual statements, particularly where the estimated pension remains unchanged, would place a disproportionate cost burden on defined benefit schemes. We have no plans to require schemes to issue such statements.</p>","Hexham","Guy Opperman",,"2017-09-15T13:27:01.713Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759458/answer","Biography information for Guy Opperman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759458/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759458/answer",,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-11","Occupational Pensions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, if he will change current regulations so that employers are required to issue annual automatic pension statements.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","9730"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759459","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-09-18","<p>The average waiting times for Employment Tribunal hearings in 2016/17 for Wales is 28 weeks. Information broken down specifically for Employment Tribunals in North Wales waiting times is not recorded.</p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee",,"2017-09-18T13:08:20.28Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759459/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759459/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759459/answer",,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-09-11","Employment Tribunals Service: North Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, for what reasons there is an average waiting time of 34 weeks for a tribunal date in North Wales; and what the longest time is for which a person has had to wait for such a date.","false","Biography information for Chris Ruane","Vale of Clwyd","Chris Ruane","9719"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759460","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-14","<p>I refer the Right Honourable Member to the answer I gave on 11 September 2017 to questions <a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Commons/2017-09-04/7328/" target="_blank">7328</a>, <a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Commons/2017-09-04/7329/" target="_blank">7329</a>, <a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Commons/2017-09-04/7431/" target="_blank">7431</a>, <a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Commons/2017-09-05/8923/" target="_blank">8923</a> and <a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Commons/2017-09-06/9191/" target="_blank">9191</a>.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-09-14T14:16:55.927Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759460/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759460/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759460/answer",,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-11","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many and what proportion of universal credit recipients have waited over six weeks for their first payment.","false","Biography information for Sir Vince Cable","Twickenham","Sir Vince Cable","9774"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759461","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-09-18","<p>The panel member resource for the Employment Tribunals hearings in Wales is managed across Wales on a case by case basis. No cases are delayed due to lack of panel members.</p><p> </p><p>The Regional Judge keeps this under close monitoring and currently the overall resource in Wales is sufficient to deploy judiciary to meet demand on a case by case basis.</p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee",,"2017-09-18T13:09:30.517Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759461/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759461/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759461/answer",,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-09-11","Employment Tribunals Service: North Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what steps are being taken to address the shortage of panel members needed for tribunals in the North Wales area.","false","Biography information for Chris Ruane","Vale of Clwyd","Chris Ruane","9776"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759462","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-09-14","<p>The Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy collect data from energy companies on the price of energy. This data is collected in confidence and therefore cannot be provided by individual supplier.</p><p>In real terms, the cost of an average annual UK domestic energy bill based on fixed consumption levels[1] for combined gas and standard electricity increased year on year from 2010 to 2014 but fell between 2014 and 2016. Overall from 2010 to 2016, bills increased by 8.4 per cent, assuming fixed consumption. However, over this time period average household consumption of gas and electricity also fell, in large part as a result of improved energy efficiency. Based on actual consumption, bills were slightly lower in 2016 than 2010, although this reflects colder than average temperatures in 2010.</p><p>Data based on fixed consumption can be found online at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/annual-domestic-energy-price-statistics" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/annual-domestic-energy-price-statistics</a>. Information on the impact of variable consumption can be found here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/604317/Domestic_energy_bills_in_2016_-_the_impact_of_variable_consumption.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/604317/Domestic_energy_bills_in_2016_-_the_impact_of_variable_consumption.pdf</a>.</p><p>Additionally, individual companies have published their total revenue from sales of domestic gas and electricity through the consolidated segmental reports which can be found here:</p><p><a href="https://www.ofgem.gov.uk/system/files/docs/2017/06/links_to_consolidated_segmental_statements_0.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.ofgem.gov.uk/system/files/docs/2017/06/links_to_consolidated_segmental_statements_0.pdf</a></p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>[1] Consumption levels: 3,800kWh for electricity and 15,000kWh for gas</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-09-14T15:18:56.04Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759462/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759462/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759462/answer",,,,,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-09-11","Energy: Prices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what estimate his Department has made of the percentage change in the cost for the average domestic dual fuel bill for customers of (a) British Gas, (b) EDF, (c) Npower, (d) E.ON, (e) Scottish Power and (f) SSE since 2010.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","9772"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759463","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-09-14","<p>The Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy (BEIS) was formed as part of the machinery of government changes in July 2017, by merging parts of BIS and parts of DECC.</p><p>The BEIS 2017 pay award has not yet been agreed, so details of staff pay increases are not available for this year.</p><p>It is also not possible to provide accurate information for pay increases for staff (a) above, (b) at and (c) less than one per cent for each of the former departments other than at disproportionate costs. This is because this will require a number of reports to be generated and checked in both former departments for staff at both Senior Civil Service level and below in relation to both the 2015 and 2016 pay awards.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-09-14T15:18:52.117Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759463/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759463/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759463/answer",,,,,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-09-11","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, how many of his Department's staff had a pay increase (a) above, (b) at and (c) less than one per cent in each of the last three years for which information is available.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","9760"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759464","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-09-14","<p>After an increase in 2013, average household dual fuel bills declined in real terms between 2013 and 2016. Actions taken to tackle emissions have helped to reduce average energy bills for households as efficiency savings have more than offset the increased cost of supporting low carbon technologies.</p><p>The Committee on Climate Change (CCC) estimate that the cost of policies delivering cleaner energy, support for vulnerable households, and investing in upgrading our buildings account for around 12 per cent (around £140) of an average household dual fuel bill in 2016. However, these costs are on average more than offset by savings from improvements to the energy efficiency of people’s homes. The CCC estimate that household energy efficiency improvements made since 2008 are delivering average bill savings of around £290 per year, driven in large part by government policy.</p><p> </p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-09-14T15:20:19.74Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759464/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759464/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759464/answer",,,,,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-09-11","Energy: Prices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what assessment he has made of the effect of Government policy on trends in the average cost of domestic dual fuel energy bills over the last five years.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","9770"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759465","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-09-14","<p>The Government is determined to deliver clean growth – cutting our emissions while growing the economy. Under this government we have seen significant investments in low carbon growth in sectors such as offshore wind, low emission vehicles, and green finance. It has been estimated that that clean energy investments in the UK have more than doubled since 2010, rising from $10.8 billion in 2010 to over $25 billion in 2016 (Bloomberg New Energy Finance, 2017).</p><p>As part of our Industrial Strategy, our investment in energy innovation will more than double to over £400 million per year by 2021. Much of this support will enable UK companies to invest in low carbon growth.</p><p>In addition, we have a range of policies in place to support UK businesses in reducing their energy use – for example through Climate Change Agreements, where businesses receive financial benefits in return for take up of energy efficiency measures.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2017-09-14T15:59:01.41Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759465/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759465/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759465/answer",,,,,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-09-11","Business: Carbon Emissions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what steps the Government is taking to provide financial help to businesses to invest in low carbon growth.","false","Biography information for Mary Glindon","North Tyneside","Mary Glindon","9835"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759466","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-09-18","<p>Since my appointment to the department in June I have met with a variety of stakeholders in the small scale renewables sector, including the Solar Trade Association, and the Renewable Energy Association.</p>","Watford","Richard Harrington",,"2017-09-18T09:45:22.787Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759466/answer","Biography information for Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759466/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759466/answer",,,,,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-09-11","Solar Power: Feed-in Tariffs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what recent discussions he has had with representatives from the solar energy industry on the future of the Feed-in Tariff scheme.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","9821"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759467","Cabinet Office","false","2017-09-14","<p>This information is not held centrally.</p><p>All public authorities are required to implement government guidelines that set out how government buyers should source steel for major projects so that the true value of UK steel is taken into account in major procurement decisions.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-09-14T13:54:23.217Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759467/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759467/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759467/answer",,,,,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-09-11","Iron and Steel: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, pursuant to the Answer of 11 September 2017 to Question 9289, on iron and steel: procurement, what progress each Government department is making in delivering greater UK steel content in line with the Government's new public procurement guidelines published in April 2016.","false","Biography information for Nic Dakin","Scunthorpe","Nic Dakin","9980"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759468","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-09-18","<p>In the Antarctic, there are two main forms of ice, glacial and sea ice, which, due to differences in measurement approaches, are assessed separately.</p><p>Sea ice, formed from freezing seawater, is highly variable on a year-to-year basis, and over the last 5 years (2012 - 2016) the annual average extent of sea ice has decreased by an average of about a quarter of a million square kilometres per year. In March 2017 the sea ice extent dropped to the lowest level observed since satellite monitoring began in 1978— at about 2 million square kilometres, or 27% below the mean annual minimum.</p><p>In the 5 years to mid-2016, around 550 Gigatonnes of glacial ice, which is formed from snow, were lost from the ice sheet.</p><p>For a full understanding of changes in Antarctic ice, longer-term trends should be assessed. The 5<sup>th</sup> Assessment Report of the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change showed that the Antarctic ice sheet has been losing mass over the past two decades and, while the long term trend in Antarctic sea ice extent has shown a small increase, there are strong regional differences, with extent increasing in some regions and decreasing in others.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2017-09-18T13:12:24.413Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759468/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759468/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759468/answer",,,,,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-09-11","Antarctic: Snow and Ice","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what assessment his Department has made of how much ice has reduced in the Antarctic in the last five years.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","9992"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759469","HM Treasury","false","2017-09-14","<p>The provision of a pre-paid funeral plan is defined as a regulated activity and falls within the Financial Conduct Authority’s regulatory remit unless specific exemption criteria are met. This arrangement and these exemption criteria are set out in the Financial Services and Markets Act 2000 (Regulated Activities) Order 2001.</p><p> </p><p>HM Treasury sets the legislative framework for the regulation of financial services, including the provision of pre-paid funeral plans, and continues to keep such exemptions under review.</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay",,"2017-09-14T13:28:26.6Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759469/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759469/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759469/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-09-11","Funerals: Regulation","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment he has made of the merits of introducing statutory regulation of pre-paid funeral plans.","false","Biography information for Liz McInnes","Heywood and Middleton","Liz McInnes","9978"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759470","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-09-15","<p>The <em>Plan for Public Procurement: Food and Catering Services</em> which was published in 2014 already provides UK food businesses with greater access to central government and wider public sector contracts.</p><p>The Plan aims to simplify the public procurement process and open up the market to more SMEs and local producers. It provides a level playing field on which UK producers can compete for the opportunity to supply more of the produce currently supplied from other countries. It includes tools such as the balanced scorecard, to help contracting parties to balance a range of criteria beneficial to the consumer, the environment, and to producers. These criteria include embedding UK production standards, encouraging seasonality of fresh produce and calling for menus which celebrate the provenance of the food. This approach is a UK-led initiative which is not affected by leaving the EU.</p><p>The balanced scorecard approach is mandated for central government departments as existing contracts come up for renewal and it is also strongly encouraged for other public sector bodies. Defra is working closely with buyers and with the industry to ensure they are well prepared to maximise the opportunities.</p><p>The UK’s departure from the EU allows us to re-examine procurement rules to ensure they work in the best interests of UK businesses.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-09-15T14:59:06.673Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759470/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759470/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759470/answer",,,,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-09-11","Food: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what plans he has to change regulations to enable local authorities or central government to stipulate that food and drink that is procured centrally must be of local country or UK origin after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Martyn Day","Linlithgow and East Falkirk","Martyn Day","9924"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759471","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-09-14","<p>The result from the contracts for difference auction is a great result for British consumers and will drive down the cost of decarbonisation. However, the strike prices for offshore wind and nuclear are not directly comparable given the differences in the characteristics of the technologies. Having a diverse generation mix is important for the UK’s security of supply. Nuclear also has a key role to play as part of a diverse generation mix delivering reliable low carbon electricity for consumers.</p><p> </p>","Watford","Richard Harrington",,"2017-09-14T09:09:17.1Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759471/answer","Biography information for Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759471/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759471/answer",,,,,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-09-11","Wind Power: Seas and Oceans","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, whether he plans to prioritise investment in offshore wind energy over nuclear energy in light of recent figures that shows that energy from offshore wind will now be cheaper.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","9937"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759472","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-09-18","<p>The Renewable Heat Incentive Scheme and Domestic Renewable Heat Incentive Scheme (Amendment) (No. 2) Regulations 2017 were laid before Parliament on 30 August 2017. These regulations are due to come in force on 20 September 2017, subject to Parliamentary process. Further reforms outlined in the Government response in December 2016 will be implemented in due course, subject to Parliamentary process.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2017-09-18T09:52:12.353Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759472/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759472/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759472/answer",,,,,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-09-11","Renewable Heat Incentive Scheme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, in what month in 2017 he plans to reintroduce the Renewable Heat Scheme Regulations 2017.","false","Biography information for Emma Hardy","Kingston upon Hull West and Hessle","Emma Hardy","9920"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759473","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-09-18","<p>This cannot be directly determined from the application data because we do not require applicants to indicate if they own another Renewable Heat Incentive installation.</p><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2017-09-18T09:49:13.267Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759473/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759473/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759473/answer",,,,,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-09-11","Renewable Heat Incentive Scheme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, how many single applicants have received subsidies for multiple installations under the non-domestic Renewable Heat Incentive scheme since that scheme's inception.","false","Biography information for Emma Hardy","Kingston upon Hull West and Hessle","Emma Hardy","9921"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759474","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-09-18","<p>I refer the hon Member to the answer I gave to the hon Member for Huddersfield (Barry Sheerman) to Question UIN <a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Commons/2017-09-06/9047/" target="_blank">9047</a>.</p>","Watford","Richard Harrington",,"2017-09-18T09:54:34.477Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759474/answer","Biography information for Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759474/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759474/answer",,,,,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-09-11","Energy: Kingston upon Hull West and Hessle","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what procedures are in place to ensure the safe installation of smart meters in Kingston upon Hull West and Hessle constituency.","false","Biography information for Emma Hardy","Kingston upon Hull West and Hessle","Emma Hardy","9922"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759475","Department for International Trade","false","2017-09-18","<p>The Department for International Trade has received services from the Behavioural Insights Team since the department’s creation in 2016. This has enabled the department to add to its evidence base to support priority government areas.</p><p>Since January 2011, details of central government contracts above the value of £10,000 are published on Contracts Finder. Contracts published after 26 February 2015 can be viewed at: <a href="https://www.contractsfinder.service.gov.uk/Search" target="_blank">https://www.contractsfinder.service.gov.uk/Search</a>.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands","9650","2017-09-18T15:59:53.3Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759475/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759475/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759475/answer",,,,,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-09-11","Department for International Trade: Behavioural Insights Team","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what services his Department has received from the Behavioural Insights Team since his Department's creation.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","9954"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759476","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-09-20","<p>There are currently 84 UK products with geographical indication protection, including food products, wine, beers, ciders, spirit drinks and wool. A full list can be found on the protected food name scheme page on gov.uk.</p><p> </p><p>As we leave the EU, the UK will continue to abide by World Trade Organisation rules on the protection of geographical indications, and we will prioritise continued protection of the best of our UK food and drink. Countries outside the EU are already able to participate in the EU's geographical indication schemes when selling onto the EU market. In addition, the EU rules that currently govern the enforcement of geographical indications will be placed on a UK legal basis through the EU Withdrawal Bill.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-09-20T14:45:04.163Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759476/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759476/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759476/answer",,,,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-09-11","Food: Origin Marking","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what products in the UK have protected geographical indication; and what steps he is taking to guarantee that status after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Chris Ruane","Vale of Clwyd","Chris Ruane","9705"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759477","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-09-14","<p>Traditional Grimsby Smoked Fish has rightly been recognised as a Protected Food Name which celebrates the traditional method of production, local provenance and the skills of those involved. Countries outside the EU are already able to participate in the EU's Protected Food Name scheme when selling onto the EU market. In addition, the EU rules that currently govern the enforcement of Protected Food Names will be placed on a UK legal basis through the EU Withdrawal Bill. The UK will continue to abide by WTO rules on the protection of geographical indications globally.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-09-14T15:30:26.267Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759477/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759477/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759477/answer",,,,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-09-11","White Fish: Origin Marking","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what steps he has taken to protect the status of Great Grimsby smoked haddock after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Melanie Onn","Great Grimsby","Melanie Onn","9845"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759478","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-09-14","<p>The Department for Exiting the European Union is committed to ensuring that we access the very best scientific expertise. There are several models for achieving this and we must be sure we take into account DExEU’s role as a co-ordinating department. We are currently exploring these options, including considering the appointment of a Chief Scientific Adviser.</p>","Wycombe","Mr Steve Baker",,"2017-09-14T10:22:16.06Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759478/answer","Biography information for Mr Steve Baker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759478/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759478/answer",,,,,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-09-11","Department for Exiting the European Union: Chief Scientific Advisers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, if his Department will appoint a chief scientific advisor.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","9857"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759479","Department for Exiting the European Union ","false","2017-09-19","<p>The Department for Exiting the European Union has met a number of stakeholders from the agricultural sector, including the National Farmers Union, National Pig Association, the Country Land and Business Association and the International Meat Trade Association.</p><p>The Government is also working closely with the Devolved Administrations. The Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs is meeting his ministerial counterparts in the Welsh and Scottish Governments, along with a senior official from the Northern Ireland Executive Department of Agriculture, Environment and Rural Affairs, in late September for on-going discussions on the UK’s withdrawal from the EU. Further joint ministerial meetings will take place on a regular basis, as well as continued bilateral discussions.</p><p> </p>","Wycombe","Mr Steve Baker",,"2017-09-19T14:44:08.17Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759479/answer","Biography information for Mr Steve Baker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759479/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759479/answer",,,,,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union ","Exiting the European Union ","2017-09-11","Agriculture","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, what meetings his Department has had with (a) farming unions and (b) devolved administrations to discuss matters relating to farming since June 2016.","false","Biography information for Chris Ruane","Vale of Clwyd","Chris Ruane","9923"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759480","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-09-19","<p>The Department for Exiting the European Union has not received any services from the Behavioural Insights Team since its creation.</p><p> </p>","Wycombe","Mr Steve Baker",,"2017-09-19T14:42:23.28Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759480/answer","Biography information for Mr Steve Baker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759480/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759480/answer",,,,,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-09-11","Department for Exiting the European Union: Behavioural Insights Team","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, what services his Department has received from the Behavioural Insights Team since his Department's creation.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","9953"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759481","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-09-14","<p>All departments are equipping themselves with the resources they need to get the best deal for the UK. The Department for Exiting the European Union now has over 450 staff based in the UK plus the expertise of over 120 officials in Brussels. We regularly review headcount to ensure we are appropriately staffed to deal with all aspects of the negotiations.</p><p><br>The Department is continuing to recruit the brightest and the best from across the civil service, the wider public sector and the private sector. Numbers are regularly changing and our aim is to have a streamlined Department, while hiring in the right skills and experience to get the best outcome for the UK.</p>","Wycombe","Mr Steve Baker",,"2017-09-14T10:23:42.407Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759481/answer","Biography information for Mr Steve Baker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759481/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759481/answer",,,,,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-09-11","Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, what plans he has to recruit more officials to assist with the negotiations on the UK leaving the EU; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","10011"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759603","Attorney General","false","2017-09-14","<p>The CPS prosecutes cases where they meet the test for prosecution. It allocates its resources accordingly and will continue to do so.</p><p> </p><p>I welcome the CPS’s commitment to treat hate crimes using social media as seriously as other sorts of hate crime.</p><p> </p>","South Swindon","Robert Buckland",,"2017-09-14T12:34:38.267Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759603/answer","Biography information for Robert Buckland","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759603/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759603/answer",,,,,,,,"88","Attorney General","Attorney General","2017-09-11","Hate Crime: Social Networking","1","House of Commons","To ask the Attorney General, what steps the Government is taking to ensure that the Crown Prosecution Service has adequate resources to tackle social media hate crime.","false","Biography information for Emma Hardy","Kingston upon Hull West and Hessle","Emma Hardy","900856"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760332","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-09-14","<p>I refer the Hon. member to my response to question from the member for Lewisham Deptford in the chamber this morning.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2017-09-14T13:23:43.063Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760332/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760332/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760332/answer",,,,,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-09-11","Sports: Discrimination","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what steps her Department is taking to tackle discrimination in sport.","false","Biography information for Alex Norris","Nottingham North","Alex Norris","900849"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760333","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-09-14","<p>Superfast Broadband is now available to nearly 94% of premises in the UK and is on track to reach 95% by the end of 2017. Reinvestment of efficiency savings and gainshare from the government programme, coupled with further commercial roll out, means that coverage can increase. By 2020, we will ensure universal broadband availability of at least 10Mbps, so that no home or business is left behind.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-09-14T17:01:04.607Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760333/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760333/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760333/answer",,,,,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-09-11","Broadband: Rural Areas","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what plans her Department has to improve broadband provision in rural areas in the next five years.","false","Biography information for Paula Sherriff","Dewsbury","Paula Sherriff","900850"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760334","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-09-14","<p>I refer the hon member to my response to the question from the member from Orkney and Shetland during DCMS questions today in the chamber.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock","7202","2017-09-14T16:58:48.223Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760334/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760334/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760334/answer",,,,,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-09-11","Broadband: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what discussions she has had with the Scottish Government on the roll-out of superfast broadband.","false","Biography information for Mr Alistair Carmichael","Orkney and Shetland","Mr Alistair Carmichael","900848"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760335","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-09-14","<p>Ensuring that the UK's digital and technology sectors remain strong and at the forefront of international innovation and enterprise are priorities for this Government</p><p><br> Since the 2016 referendum, we have carried out extensive and diverse engagement with hundreds of businesses of all sizes across the UK on the potential implications of our withdrawal from the EU, alongside extensive wider analysis and engagement.</p><p> </p><p>Investment continues to flow into the UK’s tech businesses as they go from strength to strength. Only yesterday, FinTech start-up Neyber received a huge £100m boost.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-09-14T16:59:48.147Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760335/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760335/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760335/answer",,,,,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-09-11","Digital Technology","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what assessment she has made of the potential effect of the UK leaving the EU on the digital and tech industries.","false","Biography information for Martin Whitfield","East Lothian","Martin Whitfield","900846"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758949","Attorney General","false","2017-09-19","<p>The CPS has met the Behavioural Insights Team as part of a project to encourage higher rates of defendant engagement with the CJS but have made no payment to the team.</p><p>Otherwise, the Law Officers’ Departments have not received services from the Behavioural Insights Team.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","South Swindon","Robert Buckland",,"2017-09-19T15:39:54.6Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758949/answer","Biography information for Robert Buckland","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758949/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758949/answer",,,,,,,,"88","Attorney General","Attorney General","2017-09-08","Attorney General: Behavioural Insights Team","1","House of Commons","To ask the Attorney General, what services the Law Officers' Departments has received from the Behavioural Insights Team since 2014.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","9673"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758950","Cabinet Office","false","2017-09-13","<p>The number of non-payroll employees (staff loaned or seconded in who remain on their parent organisation payroll) in my Department in each year since 2010-11 is shown in the table below:</p><p><strong> </strong></p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>2010/11</p></td><td><p>2011/12</p></td><td><p>2012/13</p></td><td><p>2013/14</p></td><td><p>2014/15</p></td><td><p>2015/16</p></td><td><p>2016/17</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>93</p></td><td><p>136</p></td><td><p>181</p></td><td><p>186</p></td><td><p>127</p></td><td><p>127</p></td><td><p>121</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p><strong> </strong></p><p>Audited information about the numbers of contractors working in the Department is published in the Cabinet Office Annual Report and Accounts. These are available on the Cabinet Office website at <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/cabinet-office-annual-reports-and-accounts" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/cabinet-office-annual-reports-and-accounts</a></p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>My Department seeks to make the best use of staff and resources to deliver the Government’s objectives in a way that represents value for money for the taxpayer. This includes interchange with other Government Departments and other sectors, and an appropriate mix of employment contract types that meet the needs of the business.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-09-13T14:24:19.11Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758950/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758950/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758950/answer",,,,,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-09-08","Cabinet Office: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, if he will publish the number of his Department's employees who have been employed other than in his Department's payroll in each year since 2010-11.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","9697"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758951","Cabinet Office","false","2017-09-13","<p>The Government is committed to strengthening the UK's response to bribery, corruption, money laundering, fraud and other forms of economic crime. The Government is continuing to review options to improve the effectiveness of the UK's response to economic crime, and any measures resulting from this work will be announced in due course.</p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore",,"2017-09-13T16:09:55.773Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758951/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758951/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758951/answer",,,,,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-09-08","Fraud","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, when he plans to publish the findings of his Department's economic crime review.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","9641"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758952","Cabinet Office","false","2017-09-14","<p>The Cabinet Office has received services from the Behavioural Insights Team (BIT) since 2014. This has enabled the department to add to its evidence base to support priority government areas.</p><p> </p><p>Since January 2011, details of central government contracts above the value of £10,000 are published on Contracts Finder. Contracts published prior to 26 February 2015 can be viewed at:</p><p><a href="https://data.gov.uk/data/contracts-finder-archive" target="_blank">https://data.gov.uk/data/contracts-finder-archive</a></p><p>Those published after 26 February 2015 can be viewed at:</p><p><a href="https://www.contractsfinder.service.gov.uk/Search" target="_blank">https://www.contractsfinder.service.gov.uk/Search</a></p><p> </p><p>BIT was made into a social purpose company in 2014 and is part owned by the Cabinet Office.</p><p> </p><p>BIT’s Articles of Association restricts the type of work that the organisation can undertake to that which promotes the public good. The Articles of Association can be viewed here:</p><p><a href="https://beta.companieshouse.gov.uk/company/08567792" target="_blank">https://beta.companieshouse.gov.uk/company/08567792</a></p><p> </p><p>The Cabinet Office has a representative Board member on BIT’s Board, which meets regularly (on average once per month) and is provided with detailed information on BIT’s clients via the monthly Board pack.</p><p> </p><p>The Crown Commercial Service Behavioural Insights Consulting and Research Framework Agreement contains a conflicts of interest provision. This can be viewed at:</p><p><a href="https://ccs-agreements.cabinetoffice.gov.uk/contracts/rm3742" target="_blank">https://ccs-agreements.cabinetoffice.gov.uk/contracts/rm3742</a></p><p> </p><p>We are not in a position to provide information about staff or organisational decisions of Behavioural Insights Team Limited, due to commercial confidentiality.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes","9181 ; 9193 ; 9199 ; 9200 ; 9201 ; 9202 ; 9204","2017-09-14T13:22:19.867Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758952/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758952/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758952/answer",,,,,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-09-08","Cabinet Office: Behavioural Insights Team","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what services his Department has received from the Behavioural Insights Team since 2014.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","9674"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758953","Department for Transport","false","2017-09-18","<p>The Department’s assessment of the business case for the Crossing, which included a consideration of the overall effects of tolling levels on road users, showed that the new Crossing will reduce congestion and improve journey times for users. Tolling levels for the new Mersey Gateway Crossing are the responsibility of Halton Borough Council. Any assessment of the local impact of these tolls is a matter for the Council rather than this Department.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-09-18T09:03:29.75Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758953/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758953/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758953/answer",,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-09-08","Mersey Gateway Bridge: Tolls","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether he has made an assessment of the economic effect on people reaching their place of work of toll charges on the Merseygateway Project.","false","Biography information for Mike Amesbury","Weaver Vale","Mike Amesbury","9654"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758954","HM Treasury","false","2017-09-13","<p>A total of around £9.3 billion was paid in income tax, capital gains tax and national insurance contributions by non-domiciled taxpayers in the tax year 2013-14.</p><p> </p><p>This information and further details on non-domiciled taxpayers can be found in Table 1 of ‘Statistics on Non-domiciled Taxpayers in the UK,’ on the gov.uk website (<a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/640900/Statistic_tables_on_non-domiciled_UK_taxpayers.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/640900/Statistic_tables_on_non-domiciled_UK_taxpayers.pdf</a>).</p><p> </p><p>Information on tax paid by non-domiciled taxpayers is collected through the self-assessment tax form. Data for 2016-17 is currently unavailable because the filing deadline of 31/01/2018 for 2016-17 self-assessment returns has not yet passed.</p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride",,"2017-09-13T16:28:52.403Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758954/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758954/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758954/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-09-08","Taxation: Domicil","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what estimate he has made of the tax paid by non-doms in the UK in (a) 2013-14 and (b) 2016-17.","false","Biography information for John Redwood","Wokingham","John Redwood","9661"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758955","HM Treasury","false","2017-09-13","<p>Annual growth rates are calculated from the annual average level of a variable.</p><p> </p><p>The independent Office for National Statistics publish the official estimates of UK GDP growth. The latest information can be found here: <a href="https://www.ons.gov.uk/economy/grossdomesticproductgdp/timeseries/ihyp/pn2" target="_blank">https://www.ons.gov.uk/economy/grossdomesticproductgdp/timeseries/ihyp/pn2</a></p><p> </p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay",,"2017-09-13T15:10:18.67Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758955/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758955/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758955/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-09-08","Economic Growth","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what annual growth rate results from (a) 0.2 per cent growth in Q1, (b) 0.6 per cent in Q2, (c) 0.6 per cent in Q3 and (d) 0.7 per cent in Q4.","false","Biography information for John Redwood","Wokingham","John Redwood","9662"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758956","HM Treasury","false","2017-09-13","<p>The proportion of staff in his Department which are (a) female, (b) BAME and (c) part time can be found in the link below:-</p><p><a href="https://www.ons.gov.uk/employmentandlabourmarket/peopleinwork/publicsectorpersonnel/datasets/civilservicestatisticsdatasummarytool" target="_blank">https://www.ons.gov.uk/employmentandlabourmarket/peopleinwork/publicsectorpersonnel/datasets/civilservicestatisticsdatasummarytool</a></p><p> </p><p>The proportion of the staff in his Department who received an annual performance award in each of those categories above for the last three years can be found in the table below:-</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td colspan="4"><p>Box 1 Performance Award as percentage each diverse group in scope (Award is limited to 25% of staff)</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>Female</p></td><td><p>BAME</p></td><td><p>Part-time</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014/15</p></td><td><p>54%</p></td><td><p>16%</p></td><td><p>6%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015/16</p></td><td><p>51%</p></td><td><p>16%</p></td><td><p>6%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016/17</p></td><td><p>52%</p></td><td><p>19%</p></td><td><p>5%</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>*Please note:- SCS are not included in the above table as they appraised by a separate Performance Management system set by the Cabinet Office. Also box mark 1 is only available to the top 25% of staff.</p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2017-09-13T13:54:05.603Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758956/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758956/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758956/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-09-08","Treasury: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what proportion of staff in his Department are (a) female, (b) BAME and (c) part time; and what proportion of the staff in his Department who received an annual performance award were in each of those categories in each of the last three years for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Kirsty Blackman","Aberdeen North","Kirsty Blackman","9664"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758957","HM Treasury","false","2017-09-13","<p>The British Business Bank published an assessment of the level of lending through banks and peer-to-peer providers to small and medium-sized businesses in its report on Small Business Finance Markets in February 2017.</p><p> </p><p>The report can be found at <a href="http://british-business-bank.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2017/02/BBB-SBFM-REPORT-2016-17-web.pdf" target="_blank">http://british-business-bank.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2017/02/BBB-SBFM-REPORT-2016-17-web.pdf</a></p><p> </p><p>The Government also monitors the Bank of England’s Money and Credit statistical releases and other statistical publications.</p><p> </p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay",,"2017-09-13T15:06:09.447Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758957/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758957/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758957/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-09-08","Financial Services","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, pursuant to the Answer of 5 September 2017 to Question 6054, on financial services, if he will make an assessment of the level of lending through (a) banks and (b) peer-to-peer providers to small and medium-sized businesses; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Bill Esterson","Sefton Central","Bill Esterson","9635"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758958","HM Treasury","false","2017-09-13","<p>We do not currently collect data on 'employee number' from delivery partners who provide peer-to-peer lending. We are unable to obtain robust data because it is not included in the mandatory information required by some peer-to-peer delivery partners when lending through their platforms.</p><p> </p><p>However, by their very nature, the vast majority of lending will be to organisations that have less than 50 employees.</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay",,"2017-09-13T15:05:05.11Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758958/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758958/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758958/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-09-08","Crowdfunding","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, pursuant to the Answer of 5 September 2017 to Question 6055, on crowdfunding, how much of the £120 million channelled by the British Business Bank to UK businesses through peer-to-peer platforms has been allocated to businesses which employ fewer than (a) 50 and (b) 10 people.","false","Biography information for Bill Esterson","Sefton Central","Bill Esterson","9636"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758959","HM Treasury","false","2017-09-13","<p>The Government believes that the peer-to-peer (P2P) lending sector already provides competition to the lending marketplace, and welcomes the strong growth of the industry.</p><p> </p><p>The Government has supported the sector through implementing a proportionate, principles based regime for P2P lending that balances the need for consumer protection with allowing the sector to grow and evolve.</p><p> </p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay",,"2017-09-13T15:07:56.497Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758959/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758959/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758959/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-09-08","Crowdfunding","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, pursuant to the Answer of 5 September 2017 to Question 6053, on crowdfunding, what estimate he has made of the volume of peer-to-peer lending which would provide competition to the marketplace.","false","Biography information for Bill Esterson","Sefton Central","Bill Esterson","9637"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758960","HM Treasury","false","2017-09-13","<p>The £425 million Capability and Innovation Fund is made up of 15 separate awards that eligible challenger banks and other financial service providers can compete for. These awards will range from £5 million to £120 million.</p><p> </p><p>We will be releasing further details on the Capability and Innovation Fund once the European Commission have announced their final decision.</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay",,"2017-09-13T15:02:56.59Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758960/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758960/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758960/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-09-08","Capability and Innovation Fund","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, pursuant to the Answer of 5 September 2017 to Question 6052, what proportion of the £425 million Capability and Innovation Fund will be made available to (a) challenger banks and (b) other financial services providers.","false","Biography information for Bill Esterson","Sefton Central","Bill Esterson","9638"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758961","HM Treasury","false","2017-09-13","<p>The Government has not made an estimate of the additional costs to lenders or business customers that would be created by setting rules on the level of business lending allowed through non-bank finance providers.</p><p> </p><p>The Government monitors the level of business lending through both bank and non-bank finance providers, working with both the British Business Bank and the financial regulators.</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay",,"2017-09-13T15:04:03.19Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758961/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758961/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758961/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-09-08","Crowdfunding","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, pursuant to the Answer of 5 September 2017 to Question 6051, what estimate he has made of the additional costs to (a) lenders and (b) business customers that would be created by setting rules on the level of business lending allowed through non-bank finance providers.","false","Biography information for Bill Esterson","Sefton Central","Bill Esterson","9639"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758962","HM Treasury","false","2017-09-18","<p>There is nothing in current legislation in the Reinsurance (Acts of Terrorism) Act 1993 that prevents insurers from offering terrorism insurance beyond property damage to businesses, and indeed such products exist on the market.</p><p> </p><p>It is up to businesses to decide what risks they would like to be insured against, and for insurers to assess the extent of the risks they are willing to cover. The Government does not generally intervene in these commercial decisions by businesses and insurers.</p><p> </p><p>That said, we remain in discussions with the insurance industry, Pool Re and other interested parties to ensure that the 1993 Reinsurance Act continues to enable appropriate terrorism cover to be available for all businesses in the UK.</p><p> </p><p>I am due to meet the Honourable Member shortly and I am happy to discuss his questions in further detail.</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay","9694 ; 9695","2017-09-18T11:09:50.95Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758962/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758962/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758962/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-09-08","Business: Terrorism","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether the Government plans to require insurance companies to offer terrorism insurance on all business policies.","false","Biography information for Neil Coyle","Bermondsey and Old Southwark","Neil Coyle","9689"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758963","HM Treasury","false","2017-09-18","<p>There is nothing in current legislation in the Reinsurance (Acts of Terrorism) Act 1993 that prevents insurers from offering terrorism insurance beyond property damage to businesses, and indeed such products exist on the market.</p><p> </p><p>It is up to businesses to decide what risks they would like to be insured against, and for insurers to assess the extent of the risks they are willing to cover. The Government does not generally intervene in these commercial decisions by businesses and insurers.</p><p> </p><p>That said, we remain in discussions with the insurance industry, Pool Re and other interested parties to ensure that the 1993 Reinsurance Act continues to enable appropriate terrorism cover to be available for all businesses in the UK.</p><p> </p><p>I am due to meet the Honourable Member shortly and I am happy to discuss his questions in further detail.</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay","9689 ; 9695","2017-09-18T11:09:51.013Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758963/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758963/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758963/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-09-08","Business: Terrorism","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether the Government plans to introduce legislation to update the Reinsurance (Acts of Terrorism) Act 1993 to enable insurance companies to offer terrorism insurance beyond property damage to businesses.","false","Biography information for Neil Coyle","Bermondsey and Old Southwark","Neil Coyle","9694"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758964","HM Treasury","false","2017-09-18","<p>There is nothing in current legislation in the Reinsurance (Acts of Terrorism) Act 1993 that prevents insurers from offering terrorism insurance beyond property damage to businesses, and indeed such products exist on the market.</p><p> </p><p>It is up to businesses to decide what risks they would like to be insured against, and for insurers to assess the extent of the risks they are willing to cover. The Government does not generally intervene in these commercial decisions by businesses and insurers.</p><p> </p><p>That said, we remain in discussions with the insurance industry, Pool Re and other interested parties to ensure that the 1993 Reinsurance Act continues to enable appropriate terrorism cover to be available for all businesses in the UK.</p><p> </p><p>I am due to meet the Honourable Member shortly and I am happy to discuss his questions in further detail.</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay","9689 ; 9694","2017-09-18T11:09:51.077Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758964/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758964/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758964/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-09-08","Business: Terrorism","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will make it his policy to introduce legislation to update the Reinsurance (Acts of Terrorism) Act 1993 to enable insurance companies to pay compensation to businesses after terrorism attacks when there is no damage to property.","false","Biography information for Neil Coyle","Bermondsey and Old Southwark","Neil Coyle","9695"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758965","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-09-13","<p>The Government will consider these issues in light of the Independent Review on Building Regulations and Fire Safety, the findings of the Public Inquiry and ongoing work to review building safety.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-09-13T16:14:48.57Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758965/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758965/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758965/answer",,,,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-09-08","Buildings: Fire Prevention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what recent assessment he has made of the adequacy of (a) building regulations concerning fire safety and (b) fire safety guidance for commercial and domestic planning applications used by fire services and local authorities' planning departments.","false","Biography information for Emma Reynolds","Wolverhampton North East","Emma Reynolds","9696"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758966","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-10-18","<p>Tower blocks that are currently under construction or are due to begin construction will be subject to Building Regulations. As such their design will be assessed and then the work will be inspected by independent building control bodies. The Department has commissioned and published the results of a series of BS8414 external wall system fire tests in order to improve the evidence available to developers and building control bodies in determining reasonable compliance with relevant Building Regulations. The test results and commentary from the Expert Panel advising Government can be found at the link below:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/guidance/building-safety-programme" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/guidance/building-safety-programme</a></p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/643281/Update_and_consolidated_advice_for_building_owners_following_large-scale_testing.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/643281/Update_and_consolidated_advice_for_building_owners_following_large-scale_testing.pdf</a></p><p> </p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-10-18T14:47:05.533Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758966/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758966/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758966/answer","Reading West","Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758966/answer/previousversion/11501","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758966/answer/previousversion/11501",,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-09-08","High Rise Flats: Fire Prevention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what assessment has been made of the fire resistance of residential tower blocks that are (a) under construction or (b) due to begin construction soon in light of the Grenfell Tower fire.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","9698"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758967","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-10-05","<p>The Government will consider these issues in light of the Independent Review on Building Regulations and Fire Safety, the findings of the Public Inquiry and on going work to review building safety.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-10-05T15:45:05.5Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758967/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758967/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758967/answer","Reading West","Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758967/answer/previousversion/11497","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758967/answer/previousversion/11497",,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-09-08","Social Rented Housing: Fire Alarms","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, whether his Department plans to publish new advice and regulations on the installation of mandatory fire alarms in communal areas of public housing.","false","Biography information for Emma Reynolds","Wolverhampton North East","Emma Reynolds","9671"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758968","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-10-06","<p>The Government will consider this issue in light of the Independent Review on Building Regulations and Fire Safety, the findings of the Public Inquiry and on going work to review building safety.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-10-06T14:32:11.833Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758968/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758968/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758968/answer","Reading West","Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758968/answer/previousversion/11499","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758968/answer/previousversion/11499",,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-09-08","High Rise Flats: Fire Extinguishers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what plans his Department has to require sprinklers to be installed inside all tower blocks, including in privately-owned tower blocks in (a) Wolverhampton and (b) England.","false","Biography information for Emma Reynolds","Wolverhampton North East","Emma Reynolds","9672"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758969","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-09-15","<p>My Department has already published this information on the GOV.UK website and this can be found at the link below</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/dclg-spending-over-250" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/dclg-spending-over-250</a></p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","9182","2017-09-15T12:55:41.82Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758969/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758969/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758969/answer",,,,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-09-08","Department for Communities and Local Government: Behavioural Insights Team","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what services his Department has received from the Behavioural Insights Team since 2014.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","9675"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758970","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-09-14","<p>DCMS has received services from the Behavioural Insights Team since 2014. This has enabled the department to add to its evidence base to support priority government areas.</p><p> </p><p>Since January 2011, details of central government contracts above the value of £10,000 are published on Contracts Finder. Contracts published prior to 26 February 2015 can be viewed at:</p><p> </p><p>https://data.gov.uk/data/contracts-finder-archive</p><p> </p><p>Those published after 26 February 2015 can be viewed at:</p><p>https://www.contractsfinder.service.gov.uk/Search</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock","9183","2017-09-14T16:42:58.17Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758970/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758970/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758970/answer",,,,,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-09-08","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport: Behavioural Insights Team","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what services her Department has received from the Behavioural Insights Team since 2014.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","9676"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758971","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-09-13","<p>The Museums Review is in its end stages following an extensive period of research, analysis and sector engagement around the emerging recommendations. The Department is presently engaged in securing the necessary clearances for publication, and expects to publish in the Autumn.</p>","Salisbury","John Glen",,"2017-09-13T15:21:51.797Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758971/answer","Biography information for John Glen","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758971/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758971/answer",,,,,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-09-08","Museums and Galleries: Reviews","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, when she plans to publish the Museums Review.","false","Biography information for Kevin Brennan","Cardiff West","Kevin Brennan","9643"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758972","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-13","<p>A broader impact assessment covering the latest welfare reform changes that were brought in under the Welfare Reform Act 2016, was published and can be found at <a href="http://services.parliament.uk/bills/2015-16/welfarereformandwork/documents.html" target="_blank">http://services.parliament.uk/bills/2015-16/welfarereformandwork/documents.html</a>.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>As a department, the DWP takes its commitments under the Armed Forces Covenant seriously and works to ensure that Service personnel, veterans, and their families are supported and treated fairly. DWP has put in place a number of measures to improve access to benefits and employment and to take account of the particular challenges some members of the Armed Forces community might face.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2017-09-13T13:43:54.297Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758972/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758972/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758972/answer",,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-08","Veterans: Social Security Benefits","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what assessment he has made of the financial effect of recent welfare reforms on veterans.","false","Biography information for Gavin Robinson","Belfast East","Gavin Robinson","9663"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758973","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-09-18","<p>The Ministry of Defence has made no assessment of the adequacy of support available to Service personnel from Greater Manchester who have left the Armed Forces. Support to former Service personnel residing in the UK, including Greater Manchester, is available from Statutory Authorities and the voluntary and charitable sector.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2017-09-18T14:17:03.227Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758973/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758973/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758973/answer",,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-09-08","Veterans: Great Manchester","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, whether he has made an assessment of the adequacy of support available to service personnel from Greater Manchester who have left the armed forces.","false","Biography information for Rebecca Long Bailey","Salford and Eccles","Rebecca Long Bailey","9644"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758974","Department for Education","false","2017-09-20","<p>The Government is taking the impact from the tragic Grenfell Tower fire very seriously. Building owners across the public sector estate, including schools, have been contacted to ensure any risks are managed and dealt with appropriately and promptly.</p><p>All schools must have a mandatory Fire Risk Assessment and all new schools undergo an additional check while being designed. Where sprinklers are necessary to keep staff and students safe, or where they are required under a local authority planning policy, they are fitted. There is not and has never been a national requirement for sprinklers to be fitted in all new or existing schools.</p><p>All schools have to follow strict fire safety regulations designed to ensure they are as safe as possible and well prepared in the event of a fire. They must have robust plans to follow, conduct regular fire drills, and typically have multiple exit routes.</p><p>The Government has announced an independent review of building regulations and fire safety to be led by Dame Judith Hackitt. Alongside the rest of Government, the Department will take forward any findings from the public inquiry into the Grenfell Tower fire and ensure any recommendations for schools are implemented.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2017-09-20T15:16:13.927Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758974/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758974/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758974/answer","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758974/answer/previousversion/11563","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758974/answer/previousversion/11563",,,"60","Education","Education","2017-09-08","Schools: Fire Extinguishers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what recent assessment she has made of the adequacy of regulations on sprinklers in schools.","false","Biography information for Emma Reynolds","Wolverhampton North East","Emma Reynolds","9667"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758975","Department for Education","false","2017-09-13","<p>The national rollout of 30 hours free childcare marks the delivery of a manifesto commitment that will help hundreds of thousands of hard working families. The childcare service online application has been working well for the vast majority of parents and over 216,384 valid 30 hours codes have been generated by successful applications, reaching our target for 1st September.</p><p>It is the responsibility of local authorities to assess supply and demand of free entitlement places at a local level.</p><p>The 30 hours scheme is an England only arrangement.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-09-13T15:42:23.147Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758975/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758975/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758975/answer",,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-09-08","Children: Day Care","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many 30 hours of free childcare eligibility codes were generated before the 31 August 2017 deadline in each (a) region of England and (b) constituent part of the UK.","false","Biography information for Tracy Brabin","Batley and Spen","Tracy Brabin","9642"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758976","Department for Education","false","2017-09-13","<p>We are committed to ensuring that all families have access to high quality, flexible and affordable childcare that meets the needs of working parents and supports the best outcomes for children. Extending the hours over which funded provision can be delivered, from 7.00am to 7.00pm to 6.00am to 8.00pm, means that providers can offer the 30 hours entitlement more flexibly.</p><p>Our early delivery areas have developed and tested innovative, flexible childcare approaches to support working families. In the early implementation evaluation survey, over three-quarters (78%) of parents reported that they had greater flexibility in their working life as a result of the 30 hours entitlement. Case studies showed that increased work flexibility helped parents to obtain more secure employment, enhanced career opportunities and improved their work-life balance. These approaches have been shared widely with all providers and local authorities.</p><p>We have also published practical, hands-on guidance for providers who want to work in partnership to deliver the entitlement, so that individual providers that cannot meet parents’ needs on their own can work effectively with others in order to do so.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-09-13T15:45:12.2Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758976/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758976/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758976/answer",,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-09-08","Pre-school Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, with reference to her oral contribution of 6 September 2017, Official Report, column 166, how she plans to ensure that nursery providers offer places to meet the working patterns of parents.","false","Biography information for Tracy Brabin","Batley and Spen","Tracy Brabin","9699"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758977","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-09-18","<p>The UK will continue to be bound by international Multilateral Environmental Agreements (MEAs) to which it is party. We are committed to upholding our international obligations under these agreements and will continue to play an active role internationally following our departure from the EU. We will give due consideration to the ratification of MEAs in the future to which the UK is not currently party in its own right,(recognising that some risks have no relevance to the UK.)</p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey","9691","2017-09-18T17:01:08.003Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758977/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758977/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758977/answer",,,,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-09-08","Environment: EU External Relations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what the legal position will be of international environmental agreements ratified jointly by the EU and the UK after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","9693"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758978","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-09-18","<p>The Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs has received services from the Behavioural Insights Team since 2014. This has enabled the department to add to its evidence base to support priority government areas.</p><p> </p><p>Since January 2011, details of central government contracts above the value of £10,000 have been published on Contracts Finder. Contracts published prior to 26 February 2015 can be viewed at:</p><p><a href="https://data.gov.uk/data/contracts-finder-archive" target="_blank">https://data.gov.uk/data/contracts-finder-archive</a></p><p>Those published after 26 February 2015 can be viewed at: <a href="https://www.contractsfinder.service.gov.uk/Search" target="_blank">https://www.contractsfinder.service.gov.uk/Search </a></p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice","9964","2017-09-18T14:56:09.36Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758978/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758978/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758978/answer",,,,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-09-08","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs: Behavioural Insights Team","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, how much his Department has paid to the Behavioural Insights Team in each year since 2014.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","9677"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758979","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-09-19","<p>The European Union (Withdrawal) Bill will convert the existing body of EU environmental and animal welfare law into United Kingdom law. The Government has made it clear that we intend to retain our high existing standards of animal welfare once we have left the EU. We have some of the highest animal welfare standards in the world and we intend us to remain world leaders in the future. Leaving the EU provides us with an opportunity to develop gold standard policies on animal welfare.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-09-19T14:48:56.167Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758979/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758979/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758979/answer",,,,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-09-08","Livestock: Animal Welfare","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what plans he has to maintain welfare standards for farm animals after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Daniel Kawczynski","Shrewsbury and Atcham","Daniel Kawczynski","9645"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758980","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-09-19","<p>The government intends to retain our existing high standards of animal welfare once we have left the European Union. Defra is exploring how the principles of Article 13 of the Treaty of the Functioning of the European Union can apply in the United Kingdom after we have left the European Union. Currently the European Union (Withdrawal) Bill will convert the existing body of direct European Union animal welfare law into United Kingdom law, and this European Union law takes into account the principles of Article 13.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-09-19T14:56:42.487Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758980/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758980/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758980/answer",,,,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-09-08","Animal Welfare: EU Law","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, whether he plans to recognise animals as sentinent beings in legislation, as in the Lisbon Treaty, after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Daniel Kawczynski","Shrewsbury and Atcham","Daniel Kawczynski","9690"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758981","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-09-18","<p>The UK will continue to be bound by international Multilateral Environmental Agreements (MEAs) to which it is party. We are committed to upholding our international obligations under these agreements and will continue to play an active role internationally following our departure from the EU. We will give due consideration to the ratification of MEAs in the future to which the UK is not currently party in its own right,(recognising that some risks have no relevance to the UK.)</p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey","9693","2017-09-18T17:01:07.94Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758981/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758981/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758981/answer",,,,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-09-08","Environment: Treaties","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, which international environmental agreements to which the UK is currently a party as a consequence of ratification by the EU he plans the UK to ratify in order to maintain the current level of environmental protection after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","9691"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758982","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-10-09","<p>The Foreign and Commonwealth Office has made the below payments to the Behavioural Insights teams since 2014.</p><p>2014-15: £0</p><p>2015-16: £84,395</p><p>2016-17: £355,976</p><p>2017-18 (to date): £30,654</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2017-10-09T14:26:19.683Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758982/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758982/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758982/answer",,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-09-08","Foreign and Commonwealth Office: Behavioural Insights Team","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, how much his Department has paid to the Behavioural Insights Team in each year since 2014.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","9678"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758983","Department of Health","false","2017-09-13","<p>The Department has not undertaken an impact assessment on the National Health Service offering unpaid internships in psychology.</p><p> </p><p>The responsibility for and decision as to whether to offer internships rests with individual NHS trusts.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-09-13T10:29:16.42Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758983/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758983/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758983/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-09-08","Psychology: Work Experience","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, whether his Department has carried out an equality impact assessment on the NHS offering unpaid internships in psychology.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","9659"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758984","Department of Health","false","2017-09-13","<p>The College of Paramedics (CoP) Paramedic Evidence Based Education Project Report and Health Education England (HEE) found that paramedics could make a larger contribution to urgent and emergency care with enhanced knowledge and skills, including in dementia and mental health awareness.</p><p> </p><p>These new areas of enhanced knowledge and skills are included in the new edition of the CoP undergraduate paramedic curriculum. This curriculum must be used by all higher education institutions providing paramedic courses.</p><p> </p><p>HEE has continued to support and invest in this aspect of the paramedic skill base by funding and working alongside CoP to develop a suite of bitesize online continuing professional development modules for paramedics, including dementia and mental health awareness.</p><p> </p><p>The Paramedic Evidence Based Education Project Report can be found at:</p><p><a href="https://www.collegeofparamedics.co.uk/publications/paramedic-evidence-based-education-project-peep" target="_blank">https://www.collegeofparamedics.co.uk/publications/paramedic-evidence-based-education-project-peep</a></p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-09-13T10:31:32.847Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758984/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758984/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758984/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-09-08","Paramedical Staff: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment he has made of the adequacy of the mental health training that paramedics receive.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","9660"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758985","Department of Health","false","2017-09-13","<p>For Ministers, along with other Government Departments, the Department adheres to transparent Government guidelines and publishes quarterly returns on Ministerial meetings with external organisations. The most recent data, for 2017, is available at:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/ministerial-gifts-hospitality-travel-and-external-meetings-2017." target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/ministerial-gifts-hospitality-travel-and-external-meetings-2017.</a></p><p>For the Department as a whole, this information is not collected centrally.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price",,"2017-09-13T15:55:37.123Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758985/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758985/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758985/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-09-08","Mental Health Services: Private Sector","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, pursuant to the Answer of 6 September 2017 to Question 6693, where information is collected on the meetings his Department has had with private providers of mental health care.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","9656"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758986","Department of Health","false","2017-09-13","<p>The information is not available in the format requested.</p><p> </p><p>Information is collected on the number of transfers, not the number of individual prisoners who are transferred. An individual prisoner may undergo more than one transfer in any given time period.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price",,"2017-09-13T16:12:13.467Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758986/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758986/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758986/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-09-08","Prisoners: Mental Illness","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many prisoners waited more than 14 days for a transfer to hospital under the Mental Health Act 1983 in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","9657"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758987","Department of Health","false","2017-09-14","<p>Since 2014, the Department has made payments to Behaviour Insights Ltd totalling the following amounts in these calendar years:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Year</p></td><td><p>Total spend (£)</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014</p></td><td><p>40,285</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015</p></td><td><p>6,358</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016</p></td><td><p>43,320</p></td></tr></tbody></table>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-09-14T10:59:13.223Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758987/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758987/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758987/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-09-08","Department of Health: Behavioural Insights Team","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how much his Department has paid to the Behavioural Insights Team in each year since 2014.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","9680"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758988","Department of Health","false","2017-09-13","<p>Health Technical Memorandum (HTM) 05-02: Firecode Guidance in support of functional provisions (fire safety in the design of healthcare premises) provides guidance on the minimum standards of fire safety expected in healthcare premises to comply with Part B of Schedule 1 of the Building Regulations 2010, including the use of automatic fire suppression where necessary.</p><p> </p><p>The guidance will be reviewed following the publication of the results of the Independent Review of Building Regulations and Fire Safety, which is being led by Dame Judith Hackitt in response to the Grenfell Tower incident.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-09-13T14:44:48.153Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758988/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758988/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758988/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-09-08","Hospitals: Fire Extinguishers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what recent assessment he has made of the adequacy of regulations on sprinklers in hospitals.","false","Biography information for Emma Reynolds","Wolverhampton North East","Emma Reynolds","9666"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758989","Department of Health","false","2017-09-13","<p>NHS Improvement informs us that the income value of the Liverpool core bundle is the same in 2018/19 as 2017/18. Regarding provision of community services, the value of the contract for community health services in Liverpool for 2017/18 is £81.6 million. This matches the value of the contract for these services in 2016/17.</p><p> </p><p>NHS Improvement is currently going through a process to agree the future of Liverpool Community Health Trust, and it is anticipated that the bidders for the services will propose cost improvements.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2017-09-13T16:41:17.493Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758989/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758989/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758989/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-09-08","Health Services: Liverpool","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what estimate he has made of the level of cost improvement expected from the current Liverpool core bundle process.","false","Biography information for Rosie Cooper","West Lancashire","Rosie Cooper","9669"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758990","Department of Health","false","2017-09-13","<p>Clinical commissioning groups (CCGs) should take all reasonable steps to ensure that employees, committee members, contractors and others engaged under contract with them are aware of the requirement to inform the CCG if they are employed or engaged in, or wish to be employed or engaged in, any employment or consultancy work in addition to their work with the CCG (for example, in relation to new care model arrangements).</p><p> </p><p>The following principles and rules should be adhered to:</p><p> </p><p>- CCGs should require that individuals obtain prior permission to engage in outside employment, and reserve the right to refuse permission where it believes a conflict will arise which cannot be effectively managed;</p><p> </p><p>- Staff should declare any existing outside employment on appointment, and any new outside employment when it arises;</p><p> </p><p>- CCGs may also have legitimate reasons within employment law for knowing about outside employment of staff; even if this does not give rise to risk of a conflict. Nothing in this guidance prevents such enquiries being made.</p><p> </p><p>- CCGs should ensure that they have clear and robust organisational policies in place to manage issues arising from outside employment. In particular, it is unacceptable for pharmacy advisers or other advisers, employees or consultants to the CCG on matters of procurement to themselves be in receipt of payments from the pharmaceutical or devices sector.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>- All CCGs have a statutory duty to follow this guidance and ensure that any person involved in making a decision on the contract award has no pecuniary interest. Guidance on managing conflicts of interest is available at the following link:</p><p><a href="https://www.england.nhs.uk/wp-content/uploads/2017/06/revised-ccg-coi-guidance-jul-17.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.england.nhs.uk/wp-content/uploads/2017/06/revised-ccg-coi-guidance-jul-17.pdf</a></p><p> </p><p>- All staff National Health Service terms and conditions of service is available at the following link:</p><p><a href="http://www.nhsemployers.org/employershandbook/afc_tc_of_service_handbook_fb.pdf" target="_blank">http://www.nhsemployers.org/employershandbook/afc_tc_of_service_handbook_fb.pdf</a></p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2017-09-13T16:26:02.477Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758990/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758990/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758990/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-09-08","Health Professions: Conditions of Employment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what rules or guidance he provides to health commissioning organisations on staff of those organisations taking up employment with other organisations from which the commissioning organisation had commissioned products or services.","false","Biography information for Rosie Cooper","West Lancashire","Rosie Cooper","9670"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758991","Home Office","false","2017-09-12","<p>The Home Office remains committed to publishing information on the number of people claiming asylum on the basis of sexual orientation. Work is ongoing to assure the quality of the data for publication in line with reporting standards</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2017-09-12T16:43:39.4Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758991/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758991/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758991/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-09-08","Asylum","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many asylum claims have included reference to sexuality or gender identity in each year since 2011.","true","Biography information for Dan Carden","Liverpool, Walton","Dan Carden","9634"
