"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758794","Home Office","false","2017-09-14","<p>The Department’s revised ‘Whistleblowing and Raising a Concern’ policy was launched in November 2015 and improved access for staff to raise any concerns. The department operates a confidential central reporting hotline and email address. This is complimented by a network of officials, known as Nominated Officers, who provide support and advice to staff and through which concerns can be raised.</p><p><br> The department runs staff communication campaigns each year to encourage employees to raise relevant concerns, explaining the options for doing so and the protections in place. The next campaign is due later this month.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2017-09-14T13:33:27.747Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758794/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758794/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758794/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-09-07","Home Office: Disclosure of Information","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what steps she is taking to promote whistleblowing in her Department and agencies.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","9418"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758795","Home Office","false","2017-09-12","<p>There are currently no plans to add parents or other person’s names to children’s passports.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2017-09-12T14:25:34.767Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758795/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758795/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758795/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-09-07","Passports: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, whether her Department plans to amend children's passports to include the names of both of their parents.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","9458"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758796","Home Office","false","2017-09-12","<p>Border Force does not record the occasions on which British women are asked to prove their relationship to their children on arrival to the United Kingdom. Therefore it is not possible to provide this information.</p><p> </p><p>It is not currently mandatory for a parent or guardian to produce documentation that explains their relationship to the child they are travelling with. However, in certain circumstances, such as a parent who has a different surname to their child, Border Force advises that they carry relevant documentation that verifies the relationship.</p><p> </p><p>Border Force has a statutory duty to safeguard and promote the welfare of children entering the United Kingdom. Its officers are trained to identify safeguarding issues and, where necessary, will conduct checks to confirm the relationship between a child and the parent or guardian they are accompanied by.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","9464","2017-09-12T16:42:49.723Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758796/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758796/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758796/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-09-07","Passports: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many British women have been asked by UK Border Control to prove they were related to their children when attempting to enter the UK since 2010.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","9459"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758797","House of Commons Commission","false","2017-09-13","<p>Since the launch of data.parliament.uk in 2015 the Parliamentary Digital Service has continued to deliver improvements to the volume and quality of data about the House and hon. Member activities, with a view to publishing open data for both internal and external re-use and analysis via the new website.</p><p>The Parliamentary Digital Service has increased its expertise in working with data through new recruitment and development of existing staff. New techniques in data science are being investigated, for example machine learning, with support from colleagues in the Government Digital Service. Work is ongoing to ensure that data about Parliamentary activity is available for analysis, to help deliver internal efficiencies and to facilitate research by colleagues, in particular the House of Commons Library. To deliver the value from big data analytics it is critical that the underlying data structure schema are consistent and robust. The Parliamentary Digital Service continues to work on this key enabling data infrastructure.</p>","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake",,"2017-09-13T17:00:22.58Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758797/answer","Biography information for Tom Brake","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758797/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758797/answer",,,,,,,,"18","House of Commons Commission","House of Commons Commission","2017-09-07","House of Commons: ICT","1","House of Commons","To ask the right hon. Member for Carshalton and Wallington, representing the House of Commons Commission, what preparations the House authorities have made to apply big data analytics to House and hon. Member activities.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","9522"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758798","Department for International Development","false","2017-09-12","<p>The amount of UK Official Development Assistance (ODA) spent on humanitarian assistance in each of the last 5 years is set out in the table below. In line with the OECD Development Assistance Committee (DAC) classification, this includes expenditure on emergency response, reconstruction relief and rehabilitation, and disaster prevention and preparedness.</p><p>This expenditure covers humanitarian support overseas to both refugees and non-refugees. Detailed data is not collected to separately identify expenditure overseas solely on refugees.</p><p> </p><p>UK Official Development Assistance (ODA) for Humanitarian Assistance and support to refugees 2010 -2015, £ million</p><table><tbody><tr><td colspan="5"><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td rowspan="2"><p>Year</p></td><td colspan="2"><p>Humanitarian Assistance<sup>1,3</sup></p></td><td colspan="9"><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td colspan="2"><p>Total (£ million)</p></td><td colspan="9"><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011</p></td><td colspan="2"><p>639</p></td><td colspan="9"><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012</p></td><td colspan="2"><p>558</p></td><td colspan="9"><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013</p></td><td colspan="2"><p>1,005</p></td><td colspan="9"><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014</p></td><td colspan="2"><p>1,347</p></td><td colspan="9"><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015</p></td><td colspan="2"><p>1,496</p></td><td colspan="9"><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td colspan="9"><p> </p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p>Information on total UK ODA is available at <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/572063/statistics-on-international-development-2016a.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/572063/statistics-on-international-development-2016a.pdf</a>.</p><p> </p><p>Source: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/572063/statistics-on-international-development-2016a.pdf" target="_blank">Statistics on International Development</a></p><p>Table notes:</p><p>1.The definition for humanitarian assistance and support to refugees in the UK is set internationally by the OECD DAC.</p><p>2.Covering basic costs only for the first year of stay in the UK.</p><p>3.The figures for humanitarian assistance and refugee costs cover UK bilateral and multilateral aid.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2017-09-12T16:50:52.777Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758798/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758798/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758798/answer",,,,,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-09-07","Overseas Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what proportion of the international aid budget has been spent on (a) disaster relief and (b) refugee assistance in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Tim Loughton","East Worthing and Shoreham","Tim Loughton","9385"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758799","Department for International Development","false","2017-09-12","<p>The Prime Minister has made available £32million to support those affected by Hurricane Irma and a cross-Government response has been stood up. DFID has sent more than 40 metric tonnes of UKaid to the region including thousands of shelter kits and of solar lanterns. More supplies will be arriving throughout the month. We are also working with the Overseas Territories institutions to understand how we will move from disaster response to early recovery and long-term reconstruction. The Government will continue to do all it can to support those affected. Further details of our work are available on our website <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/organisations/department-for-international-development" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/organisations/department-for-international-development</a></p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2017-09-12T16:58:39.033Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758799/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758799/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758799/answer",,,,,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-09-07","Caribbean: Hurricanes and Tornadoes","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what steps her Department is taking to support those affected by Hurricane Irma.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","9567"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758800","Department for International Development","false","2017-09-12","<p>Government Ministers are in daily contact with the Governors of the Overseas Territories affected by Hurricane Irma as well as with our partners in the region. We are coordinating closely on needs assessments and getting UKaid in affected areas.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2017-09-12T17:16:21.287Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758800/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758800/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758800/answer",,,,,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-09-07","Caribbean: Hurricanes and Tornadoes","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what discussions she has had with her counterparts in the Overseas Territories and other Caribbean states on the humanitarian response to Hurricane Irma.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","9568"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758801","Department for International Development","false","2017-09-12","<p>The Secretary of State for International Development spoke to her US counterpart Mark Andrew Green on 11<sup>th</sup> September and our teams are coordinating closely on the response effort to territories and states affected by Hurricane Irma.</p><p> </p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2017-09-12T17:14:04.587Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758801/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758801/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758801/answer",,,,,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-09-07","Caribbean: Hurricanes and Tornadoes","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what discussions she has had with her counterpart in the US on the provision of humanitarian assistance to those territories and states affected by Hurricane Irma.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","9569"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758802","Department for International Development","false","2017-09-12","<p>The Department for International Development (DFID) has a robust process in place for reporting and managing all whistleblowing concerns. This process was recently refreshed to ensure it remains in line with Cabinet Office standards and recommended best practice. The process is managed independently by DFID’s internal audit department and has been designed to give confidence to all stakeholders to raise concerns, in line with the open and transparent culture that DFID has sought to create.</p><p>The whistleblowing reporting process is set out clearly on DFID’s external website (<a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/organisations/department-for-international-development/about#reporting-fraud" target="_blank">Reporting Fraud</a>) and in more detail within the department’s internal intranet, accessible by all staff. DFID has made civil service e-learning on fraud modules mandatory for all staff and has embedded fraud awareness components across many of its core training interventions. DFID has appointed a dedicated fraud resource across the department’s country office network to support staff on an on-going basis and keep the profile of whistleblowing high.</p><p>In additional to the regular awareness raising activities undertaken, DFID played an active role in publicising the cross civil service whistleblowing awareness week in 2016 and will do so again during September 2017.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2017-09-12T14:39:46.967Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758802/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758802/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758802/answer",,,,,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-09-07","Department for International Development: Disclosure of Information","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what steps she is taking to promote whistleblowing in her Department.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","9419"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758803","Department for International Development","false","2017-09-13","<p>The detailed plans of how these funds are going to be spent will be published on DFID department’s website once suitable implementing partners are appointed. Further details of these announcements can be found in my press releases of 31 August 2017 on modern slavery and on 30 August 2017 on humanitarian support.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2017-09-13T10:57:12.86Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758803/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758803/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758803/answer",,,,,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-09-07","Nigeria: Overseas Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, when she plans to publish a breakdown of new funding for Nigeria announced in August 2017.","false","Biography information for Kate Osamor","Edmonton","Kate Osamor","9584"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758804","Department for International Development","false","2017-09-13","<p>DFID’s In the News webpage is maintained by the existing Press Office team as part of their regular duties. There is no dedicated resource required.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2017-09-13T10:56:12.76Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758804/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758804/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758804/answer",,,,,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-09-07","Department for International Development: Internet","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what the cost including for staff of maintaining her Department's In the News webpage is annually.","false","Biography information for Kate Osamor","Edmonton","Kate Osamor","9582"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758805","Department for International Development","false","2017-09-13","<p>The 2016 Multilateral Development Review included a comprehensive assessment of every UN agency receiving more than £1 million of annual core funding from DFID.</p><p>We continue to actively monitor UN Agency performance through our membership of their Governing Boards and analysis of their results data. We are clear that where agencies consistently fail to meet our high standards, their funding is at risk. The UK is pushing hard for the UN development system to change so that it is better prepared for the challenges of the 21st Century; future funding will be linked to progress on reform.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2017-09-13T10:56:40.073Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758805/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758805/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758805/answer",,,,,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-09-07","UN Agencies: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, whether she plans to review her Department's financial contribution to any UN agencies.","false","Biography information for Kate Osamor","Edmonton","Kate Osamor","9583"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758806","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-10-09","<p>Causing criminal damage to property is a criminal offence. The court must consider making a compensation order under section 130 of the Powers of the Criminal Courts (Sentencing) Act 2000 in any case where personal injury, loss or damage has resulted from the offence. It is an operational matter for the police, following advice from the Crown Prosecution Service, to decide whether or not an offence reaches the threshold required for prosecution under the relevant legislation.</p><p> </p><p>Property owners may also bring private legal proceedings to recover an award of damages for damage caused to their property by trespassers. It is for individual property owners to decide whether to take legal action of this kind.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab",,"2017-10-09T15:15:25.103Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758806/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758806/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758806/answer",,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-09-07","Travellers: Trespass","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what steps are being taken to ensure Travellers who trespass on property pay for any criminal damages and limit the expense incurred to innocent parties.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","9590"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758807","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-09-13","<p>The following information was provided by the Ministry of Justice.</p><p> </p><p>The number of defendants proceeded against at magistrates’ courts and found guilty at all courts of offences under the Protection of Badgers Act 1992 and the Wild Mammals (Protection) Act 1996, in England and Wales, by police force area, in 2016, can be viewed in the table attached.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2017-09-13T09:18:24.82Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758807/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758807/answer","9337 9451 Table FYI.docx","9337 9451 Table FYI.docx","Table","Table","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758807/answer",,,,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-09-07","Wild Mammals (Protection) Act 1996","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, how many people were (a) proceeded against and (b) convicted of an offence under the Wild Mammals (Protection) Act 1996 in each police force area in 2016.","false","Biography information for Kerry McCarthy","Bristol East","Kerry McCarthy","9451"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758808","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-09-14","<p>The whistleblowing policy and whistleblowing awareness is regularly promoted within Ministry of Justice (MoJ) to staff so they are aware that any concerns they raise will be taken seriously, and that they will be protected and supported by the department.</p><p> </p><p>MoJ has dedicated whistleblowing intranet pages with information and guidance on the policy and details of our dedicated Nominated Officers who staff can contact directly if they do not wish to raise the concerns with their managers.</p><p> </p><p>As part of supporting Civil Service Whistleblowing Awareness Day on 21 September, MoJ will be running events for staff and promoting the importance of speaking up if there are concerns of wrong doing with internal communications articles and supporting materials.</p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee",,"2017-09-14T15:23:04.773Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758808/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758808/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758808/answer",,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-09-07","Ministry of Justice: Disclosure of Information","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what steps he is taking to promote whistleblowing in his Department and agencies.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","9421"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758809","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-10-25","<p>In 2016, there were 28 convictions in England and Wales under the Psychoactive Substances Act. Data on Psychoactive Substances prosecutions can be found on <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/criminal-justice-system-statistics-quarterly-december-2016" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/criminal-justice-system-statistics-quarterly-december-2016</a>.</p><p>The information requested for those offences involving nitrous oxide is not held centrally and could not be obtained without incurring disproportionate cost.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2017-10-25T14:38:41.187Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758809/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758809/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758809/answer",,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-09-07","Psychoactive Substances Act 2016","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many people have been prosecuted and convicted under the Psychoactive Substances Act 2016 (a) in total and (b) for offences involving nitrous oxide since the commencement of that Act.","false","Biography information for Richard Burgon","Leeds East","Richard Burgon","9455"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758810","Ministry of Justice","true","2017-09-12","<p>Numbers of units of e-cigarettes, vaping products and tobacco items sold in prisons in England and Wales in each month for the last year are as set out in the attached annex.</p><p>Prisons are rolling out the smoke free policy, subject to a series of assessments which will test the operational stability, readiness and health readiness of the prisons to implement the policy in a safe, decent and secure way. HMPPS’ health partners in England and Wales are fully involved in supporting prisoners with appropriate smoking cessation services in place.</p><p>The open estate across England and Wales has been smoke free indoors since October 2015.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2017-09-12T10:59:45.787Z","2017-09-15T15:01:43.253Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758810/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758810/answer","9456 Annex A.docx","9456 Annex A.docx","Number of Products Sold in Prisons","Number of Products Sold in Prisons","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758810/answer","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758810/answer/previousversion/11646","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758810/answer/previousversion/11646","9456 Annex A.docx","Number of Products Sold in Prisons","54","Justice","Justice","2017-09-07","Prisons: Electronic Cigarettes and Tobacco","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many (a) e-cigarettes and (b) tobacco products were sold in prison shops in each of the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Richard Burgon","Leeds East","Richard Burgon","9456"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758811","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-09-12","<p>The information requested is not held centrally.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2017-09-12T11:06:41.077Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758811/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758811/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758811/answer",,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-09-07","Prison Governors","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many prison governors have worked at two or more other prisons in the last five years.","false","Biography information for Richard Burgon","Leeds East","Richard Burgon","9457"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758812","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-09-12","<p>The following information was provided by the Ministry of Justice.</p><p> </p><p>The number of defendants proceeded against at magistrates’ courts and found guilty at all courts of offences under the Hunting Act 2004, in England and Wales, by police force area, in 2016, can be viewed in the attached table.</p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2017-09-12T13:51:56.707Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758812/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758812/answer","9465 table.pdf","9465 table.pdf","Hunting Act prosecutions","Hunting Act prosecutions","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758812/answer",,,,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-09-07","Hunting Act 2004","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, how many people were (a) proceeded against and (b) convicted of an offence under the Hunting Act 2004 in each police force area in 2016.","false","Biography information for Kerry McCarthy","Bristol East","Kerry McCarthy","9465"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758813","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-09-15","<p>Community Rehabilitation Companies (CRCs) play a crucial role in delivering probation services. We have amended CRC contracts to reflect more accurately the fixed costs of delivering services to offenders.</p><p>I laid a Written Ministerial Statement and published an open letter on 19 July 2017 which outlined these activities and reaffirmed our commitment to delivering high quality probation services.</p><p>We closely monitor and robustly manage CRCs to make sure they fulfil their contractual commitments. Data on CRC performance against service levels is published quarterly, with the latest data published in July: https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/community-performance-quarterly-and-annual-2016-to-2017. The first set of final reoffending data for offenders supervised by CRCs will be published in October 2017; thereafter data will be published quarterly.</p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee",,"2017-09-15T13:05:13.313Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758813/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758813/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758813/answer",,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-09-07","Community Rehabilitation Companies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what assessment he has made of the effectiveness and performance of community rehabilitation companies since their inception.","false","Biography information for Liz Saville Roberts","Dwyfor Meirionnydd","Liz Saville Roberts","9532"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758814","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-09-15","<p>In 2014/15 the government reformed the probation system to strengthen its focus on reducing reoffending and protecting communities. These reforms included dividing the probation caseload between Community Rehabilitation Companies (CRCs) who supervise low and medium-risk offenders and the National Probation Service (NPS) who supervise higher-risk offenders.</p><p><br>Since these reforms there have been unforeseen falls in the number of offenders sentenced to community orders, and an increase in the proportion of offenders assessed as posing a higher risk of harm. The result has been fewer offenders being referred to CRCs, leading to falls in CRC income to levels below those expected at the time of competition. It is for this reason that we took action to adjust the payment mechanism in CRC contracts so that providers’ income better reflects the fixed costs of delivering services to offenders and is less sensitive to changes in demand. As previously confirmed, this additional investment will see projected payments to CRCs still being no higher than originally budgeted for at the time of the reforms.</p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee",,"2017-09-15T13:10:36.977Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758814/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758814/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758814/answer",,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-09-07","Probation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what factors led him to conclude in July 2017 that the problems experienced as a result of the reform of the probation service were unforeseen.","false","Biography information for Liz Saville Roberts","Dwyfor Meirionnydd","Liz Saville Roberts","9533"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758815","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-09-12","<p>117 prison officers have been deployed on detached duty (DD) on average for each of the last 12 months.</p><p>Prison officers are deployed on DD under national and regional arrangements, for a number of reasons, including to fill staffing gaps in other prisons. The number deployed on DD each month varies according to operational pressures. Over the course of twelve months individuals may (through choice) be deployed on DD on more than one occasion.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2017-09-12T11:08:50.133Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758815/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758815/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758815/answer",,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-09-07","Prison Officers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many prison officers have been sent on detached duty to fill staffing gaps in other prisons in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Alex Cunningham","Stockton North","Alex Cunningham","9372"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758816","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-09-12","<p>In the 12 months to 30 June 2017, 2,640 band 3-5 prison officers joined HMPPS. Of these, 123 (4.7%) subsequently resigned from their post.</p><p>Latest information on the number of newly recruited prison officers can be found in Table 8a in the HMPPS workforce statistics bulletin, at the following link:</p><p>https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/her-majestys-prison-and-probation-service-workforce-quarterly-june-2017</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2017-09-12T11:07:43.473Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758816/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758816/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758816/answer",,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-09-07","Prison Officers: Labour Turnover","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many prison officers recruited in the last 12 months have subsequently resigned from their post.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","9373"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758817","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-09-12","<p>The Prisons and Probation Ombudsman spent approximately £1.3 M on investigations into self-inflicted deaths in 2016-17. This covers the salary costs of managers, investigators, and administrative staff including interview transcribers, family liaison officers, and fees for call-off investigators. It also includes travel and incidental expenses.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2017-09-12T11:01:52.037Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758817/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758817/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758817/answer",,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-09-07","Prisoners: Suicide","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how much the Prison and Probation Ombudsman has spent on investigations into self-inflicted deaths in 2016-17.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","9367"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758818","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-09-12","<p>The Secretary of State sets by delegated authority to officials the next review date of prisoners serving the IPP sentence and who have completed their tariff. He does so with regard to the work (including but not only courses) which the prisoner needs to complete in order to reduce his risk and so present the Parole Board with evidence to support release.</p><p>IPP offenders are entitled to be considered for release at least every two years or less once their tariff has expired. The Secretary of State may set a short review date, where the prisoner has completed risk reduction work and so has the evidence which the Parole Board needs to direct his release.</p><p>We have been working closely with the Parole Board to process these cases as quickly as possible and, earlier this year, we set up a new unit focused on this and improving the efficiency of the parole process.</p><p>This work is continuing to achieve results, with 576 IPP releases in 2016; the highest number of annual releases since the sentence became available in 2005.”</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2017-09-12T17:01:21.373Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758818/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758818/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758818/answer",,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-09-07","Prison Sentences","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, if he will give the Parole Board the authority to decide when a hearing can be held to consider the cases of those with imprisonment for public protection sentences who are still in prison.","false","Biography information for Sir Christopher Chope","Christchurch","Mr Christopher Chope","9379"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758819","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-09-12","<p>If the Hon member writes with further details I will look into the case for him.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2017-09-12T10:59:37.913Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758819/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758819/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758819/answer",,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-09-07","Prisoners' Transfers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, for what reason the recommendation from Abigail Rogers at the Public Protection Casework Section of the Parole Board in her letter dated 19 May 2017 that a prisoner be transferred to an open conditions prison has not yet been acted upon.","false","Biography information for Sir Christopher Chope","Christchurch","Mr Christopher Chope","9380"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758820","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-09-15","<p>The Secretary of State has no power to instigate a coroner-led inquest.</p><p>Usually it is the coroner, who is an independent judicial office holder, who makes the decision whether to hold an inquest or, where the issue arises, to resume a suspended inquest.</p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee",,"2017-09-15T13:04:39.887Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758820/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758820/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758820/answer",,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-09-07","David Kelly","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, if he will instigate a coroner-led inquest into the death of Dr David Kelly in 2005.","false","Biography information for Dr Matthew Offord","Hendon","Dr Matthew Offord","9311"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758821","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-09-21","<p>Prosecutions for breaches of the Building Regulations, including regulations on fire safety, are brought by local authorities. The Department for Communities and Local Government does not collect information on such prosecutions.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-09-21T11:23:33.907Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758821/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758821/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758821/answer","Reading West","Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758821/answer/previousversion/11011","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758821/answer/previousversion/11011",,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-09-07","Fire Regulations: Prosecutions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how many prosecutions have been brought for breach of fire safety building regulations in each of the last seven years.","false","Biography information for Emma Reynolds","Wolverhampton North East","Emma Reynolds","9318"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758822","Northern Ireland Office","false","2017-09-15","<p>Tourism is a devolved policy area, meaning that the Northern Ireland Executive has responsibility for the promotion and delivery of the tourism offer within Northern Ireland. Tourism Ireland is responsible for marketing the island of Ireland overseas.</p><p> </p><p>VisitBritain and Tourism Northern Ireland recently signed a partnership agreement where they will work together on specific projects to market Northern Ireland to visitors.</p><p> </p><p>Over the last decade, Northern Ireland has become a 'must-see' tourist destination, and we will continue to encourage visitors to come to experience the many wonderful sights and attractions it has to offer.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Norwich North","Chloe Smith",,"2017-09-15T10:09:29.697Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758822/answer","Biography information for Chloe Smith","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758822/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758822/answer",,,,,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2017-09-07","Tourism: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, what progress he and the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport are making to attract more visitors to Northern Ireland.","false","Biography information for Mr Peter Bone","Wellingborough","Mr Peter Bone","9341"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758823","Northern Ireland Office","false","2017-09-13","<p>The Northern Ireland Office's whistleblowing policy is made available to all staff on the Department’s intranet and regularly promoted through blogs and annual awareness days; the next planned awareness day is 21 September 2017. In addition, the Department's Management Board is committed to the highest standards of openness, honesty and accountability and has designated the lead non-executive and an executive board member with responsibility for the promotion of whistleblowing across the wider Northern Ireland Office family.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Norwich North","Chloe Smith",,"2017-09-13T11:41:28.373Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758823/answer","Biography information for Chloe Smith","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758823/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758823/answer",,,,,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2017-09-07","Northern Ireland Office: Disclosure of Information","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, what steps he is taking to promote whistleblowing in his Department.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","9422"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758824","Prime Minister","false","2017-09-12","<p>I refer the right hon. Member to the press release issued on 4 September following my meeting with Saudi Foreign Minister Adel al-Jubeir and which is available on the gov.uk website: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/news/pm-meeting-with-saudi-foreign-minister-adel-al-jubeir-4-september-2017" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/news/pm-meeting-with-saudi-foreign-minister-adel-al-jubeir-4-september-2017</a></p>","Maidenhead","Mrs Theresa May",,"2017-09-12T14:23:25.277Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758824/answer","Biography information for Mrs Theresa May","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758824/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758824/answer",,,,,,,,"23","Prime Minister","Prime Minister","2017-09-07","Yemen: Military Intervention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Prime Minister, whether she has had recent discussions with the Saudi Foreign Minister on ending the blockade of Yemen.","false","Biography information for Keith Vaz","Leicester East","Keith Vaz","9452"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758825","Prime Minister","false","2017-09-12","<p>Details of my visit to Japan including those who accompanied me on the visit can be found in the press release issued on 30 August and which is available on the gov.uk website: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/news/pm-heads-to-japan-to-build-strong-post-brexit-relationship-with-toyko" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/news/pm-heads-to-japan-to-build-strong-post-brexit-relationship-with-toyko</a></p>","Maidenhead","Mrs Theresa May",,"2017-09-12T14:24:21.9Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758825/answer","Biography information for Mrs Theresa May","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758825/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758825/answer",,,,,,,,"23","Prime Minister","Prime Minister","2017-09-07","Prime Minister: Japan","1","House of Commons","To ask the Prime Minister, which representatives of which companies accompanied her on her visit to Japan from 30 August to 1 September 2017.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","9463"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758826","Prime Minister","false","2017-09-15","<p>I have nothing further to add to the answer I gave the hon. member.</p>","Maidenhead","Mrs Theresa May",,"2017-09-15T11:50:42.343Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758826/answer","Biography information for Mrs Theresa May","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758826/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758826/answer",,,,,,,,"23","Prime Minister","Prime Minister","2017-09-07","Prime Minister: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Prime Minister, pursuant to the Answer of 20 July 2017 to Question 4882, how many advisers in her foreign affairs team are not Foreign and Commonwealth Office staff.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","9552"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758827","Prime Minister","false","2017-09-15","<p>Visits by previous Prime Ministers are a matter of public record.</p>","Maidenhead","Mrs Theresa May",,"2017-09-15T11:50:21.2Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758827/answer","Biography information for Mrs Theresa May","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758827/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758827/answer",,,,,,,,"23","Prime Minister","Prime Minister","2017-09-07","Domestic Visits: Easington","1","House of Commons","To ask the Prime Minister, what the last occasion was that a serving Prime Minister visited Easington constituency.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","9603"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758828","Prime Minister","false","2017-09-15","<p>I visit all parts of the United Kingdom regularly. Details of my visits within the United Kingdom are published on the <a href="http://gov.uk" target="_blank">gov.uk</a> website.</p>","Maidenhead","Mrs Theresa May",,"2017-09-15T11:49:39.137Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758828/answer","Biography information for Mrs Theresa May","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758828/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758828/answer",,,,,,,,"23","Prime Minister","Prime Minister","2017-09-07","Housing: Horden","1","House of Commons","To ask the Prime Minister, if she will visit Easington constituency to discuss housing issues in Horden.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","9602"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758829","Department for Transport","false","2017-09-14","<p>Network Rail have informed me that there is over 20,000 miles of track in total in the UK; with Scotland having 2,800 track miles, and Wales having over 1,400 track miles</p><p> </p><p>As a proportion by Government region, Network Rail has provided the following information:</p><p><strong> </strong></p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Region</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Proportion (%)</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Region</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Proportion (%)</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>East Midlands</p></td><td><p>8</p></td><td><p>South East</p></td><td><p>15</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Eastern</p></td><td><p>9</p></td><td><p>South West</p></td><td><p>8</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>London</p></td><td><p>8</p></td><td><p>Wales</p></td><td><p>6</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>North East</p></td><td><p>3</p></td><td><p>West Midlands</p></td><td><p>8</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>North West</p></td><td><p>11</p></td><td><p>Yorkshire and the Humber</p></td><td><p>10</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Scotland</p></td><td><p>14</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p><strong> </strong></p><p>It should be noted that railway track in each region is utilised to different intensities. For example in 2015/16 there were 537,369 thousand rail passenger journeys within the London region which was almost six times more journeys than within the North West region.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2017-09-14T14:37:16.713Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758829/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758829/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758829/answer",,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-09-07","Railway Track","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what proportion of railway track is located in each region of England and Wales.","false","Biography information for Chris Ruane","Vale of Clwyd","Chris Ruane","9355"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758830","Department for Transport","false","2017-09-14","<p>Since 2009/10 the Department has received annual rebates from Arriva Train Wales.</p><p> </p><p>Following a Control Period 4 adjustment for track access charges, payments of approximately £30 million per annum were made to the Department between 2009/10 and 2013/14 inclusive.</p><p> </p><p>A further Control Period 5 adjustment for track access charges led to rebates of approximately £60m in 2014/15, £68m in 2015/16 and £70m in 2016/17.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2017-09-14T10:18:06.707Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758830/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758830/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758830/answer",,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-09-07","Arriva Trains Wales: Rebates","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how much his Department received from Arriva Trains Wales in rebates in each year since that franchise has been in operation.","false","Biography information for Chris Ruane","Vale of Clwyd","Chris Ruane","9356"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758831","Department for Transport","false","2017-09-14","<p>The Office of Rail and Road publish railway infrastructure statistics, which contain the length of electrified route in Great Britain (including Scotland). The table below gives total electrified route length from 2009-10 to 2015-16.</p><p> </p><p>Network Rail manage the infrastructure, but they geographically organise the network by ‘Routes’ rather than by region, therefore this information is not available by region.</p><p><strong><em> </em></strong></p><p><strong><em>Route and Track Miles of the rail network in Great Britain. Source: ORR</em></strong></p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Year</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Route miles electrified</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2009-10</strong></p></td><td><p><em>3,256</em></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2010-11</strong></p></td><td><p><em>3,270</em></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2011-12</strong></p></td><td><p><em>3,270</em></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2012-13</strong></p></td><td><p><em>3,272</em></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2013-14</strong></p></td><td><p><em>3,274</em></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2014-15</strong></p></td><td><p><em>3,277</em></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2015-16*</strong></p></td><td><p><em>3,313</em></p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>*Provisional.</p><p>The above table shows that 57 route miles were electrified between 2009-10 and 2015-16.</p><p> </p><p>However, the figures above just show completed electrification works and so do not take account of the many more route miles which are in the process of being electrified. Various schemes ongoing across the country include:</p><p> </p><p>o The 120 mile Great Western Main Line route between London and Cardiff (of which the 12 mile section from West Drayton to Maidenhead was recently turned on)</p><p>o 49 mile route from Blackpool North to Manchester Piccadilly</p><p>o Just under 17 miles route from Walsall to Rugeley Trent Valley-</p><p>o 13 mile route from Gospel Oak to Barking</p><p>o Just over 4 miles at Bromsgrove-</p><p>o 1 mile at the Orsdall Chord</p><p> </p><p>All of the above is much more than the 10 miles electrified by Labour in 13 years.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2017-09-14T14:34:07.423Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758831/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758831/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758831/answer",,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-09-07","Railways: Electrification","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many miles of railway track were electrified in each region of England and Wales in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Chris Ruane","Vale of Clwyd","Chris Ruane","9357"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758832","Department for Transport","false","2017-09-14","<p>The Office of Rail and Road publish railway infrastructure statistics, which contain the total length of track in Great Britain (including Scotland) by year.</p><p> </p><p>This information is available here: <a href="http://dataportal.orr.gov.uk/displayreport/report/html/c35e0c28-324f-4168-81b9-be197963f251" target="_blank">http://dataportal.orr.gov.uk/displayreport/report/html/c35e0c28-324f-4168-81b9-be197963f251</a></p><p> </p><p>This information is not available by region.</p><p> </p><p>The year-on-year change in track length is the net change of new track added minus length of track closed. Therefore, a year-on-year increase does not necessarily equal the total length of new track added.</p><p> </p><p>Network Rail manage the infrastructure, but they geographically organise the network by ‘Routes’ rather than by region, therefore this information is not available by region.</p><p><strong><em> </em></strong></p><p><strong><em>Track Miles of the rail network in Great Britain. Source: ORR</em></strong></p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Year</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Total track miles</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2009-10</strong></p></td><td><p>19,312</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2010-11</strong></p></td><td><p>19,334</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2011-12</strong></p></td><td><p>19,306</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2012-13</strong></p></td><td><p>19,313</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2013-14</strong></p></td><td><p>19,324</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2014-15</strong></p></td><td><p>19,341</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2015-16*</strong></p></td><td><p>19,387</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>*Provisional.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2017-09-14T14:42:53.907Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758832/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758832/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758832/answer",,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-09-07","Railway Track","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many miles of new railway track were laid in each region of England and Wales in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Chris Ruane","Vale of Clwyd","Chris Ruane","9358"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758833","Department for Transport","false","2017-09-14","<p>Figures on public sector spend at a regional and national level are part of the Government’s Country and Regional Analysis (CRA) statistics. CRA statistics for all capital expenditure by central and local governments and other public bodies on rail transport are provided in the table below.</p><p> </p><p>The benefits from this spend on transport interventions will often accrue to passengers far beyond the residents of the immediate local area or region. This is particularly the case for spending on the railways which connect cities and regions across the country and delivery broader benefits beyond the region concerned. Whilst the CRA attempts to allocate expenditure on the basis of which region benefits from the spend, rather than where it is made, inevitably allocations are not always precise.</p><p> </p><p>Regarding spend in London, London has a substantial number of daily commuters and visitors, both domestically and internationally, who will be using and benefitting from the public transport networks in London but who aren’t residents in London.</p><p> </p><p>The unique scale and urban density of London by comparison to other parts of the country also means that it is particularly adapted to large scale public transport networks.</p><p> </p><p><strong><em>Public expenditure (capital) on rail by year and region, from 2009-10. Source: HMT. </em></strong></p><p><em>Nominal values in £ millions</em></p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Region</strong></p></td><td><p><strong> 2009-10</strong></p></td><td><p><strong> 2010-11</strong></p></td><td><p><strong> 2011-12</strong></p></td><td><p><strong> 2012-13</strong></p></td><td><p><strong> 2013-14</strong></p></td><td><p><strong> 2014-15</strong></p></td><td><p><strong> 2015-16</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>North East</p></td><td><p>115</p></td><td><p>109</p></td><td><p>147</p></td><td><p>156</p></td><td><p>145</p></td><t