 State for Transport, how much was invested in improving railway infrastructure in each region of England and Wales in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Chris Ruane","Vale of Clwyd","Chris Ruane","9359"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758834","Department for Transport","false","2017-09-14","<p>Both Ministers and officials of my Department have been in contact with other EU Member States regarding the increased queuing times at passport controls at Schengen borders. Whilst acknowledging the importance of security at the borders, we have urged the governments to do their utmost to ensure that the queuing times are kept as quick as possible.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2017-09-14T11:04:12.403Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758834/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758834/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758834/answer",,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-09-07","Airports: EU Countries","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what representations his Department has made to other EU member states on easing waiting times at their airports.","false","Biography information for Dr Matthew Offord","Hendon","Dr Matthew Offord","9313"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758835","Department for Transport","false","2017-09-14","<p>The Department for Transport published its Transport Investment Strategy on the 5<sup>th</sup> July 2017, which describes new rebalancing measures to deliver a stronger, fairer Britain. We want to ensure that transport investment programmes, including rail, contribute to a more balanced economy, increase productivity or growth, support new housing, improve reliability and tackle congestion.</p><p> </p><p>As described in the Strategy, the Department is developing a new assessment standard that will require investment programmes to be judged on how they contribute towards creating a more balanced economy, as part of the overall assessment of their strategic case.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2017-09-14T13:44:54.117Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758835/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758835/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758835/answer",,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-09-07","Railways: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what steps he is taking to ensure the equitable distribution of rail funding.","false","Biography information for Mr Barry Sheerman","Huddersfield","Mr Barry Sheerman","9338"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758836","Department for Transport","false","2017-09-14","<p>In terms of infrastructure, we are currently working with Rail North and Network Rail to develop very significant improvements for rail passengers on the Transpennine route with phased introduction from December 2022. The upgrade aims to deliver major reductions in journey times, the ability to run more frequent and longer trains offering more seats on both long distance and local services and improvements to overall performance on the whole route. Huddersfield will be in the heart of our plans to improve access on the Transpennine route.</p><p> </p><p>In addition, the new Northern and Transpennine franchises which commenced in April 2016 will deliver an unprecedented package of improvements including more than 500 new carriages, room for 40,000 extra passengers and more than 2,000 extra services a week. By 2020 all the trains will be brand new or completely refurbished, and all the Pacer trains will be gone.</p><p> </p><p>Planned service improvements specifically for Huddersfield include: new trains, and longer trains, with more seats and of higher quality – including free Wi-Fi, at-seat power sockets and real-time passenger information; increased number of morning peak seats by more than 50% into Manchester and Leeds; more weekend services with some earlier starts and later finishes; an extension of North TransPennine services to Edinburgh; and increased number of direct services to Hull and Newcastle.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2017-09-14T10:21:12.267Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758836/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758836/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758836/answer",,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-09-07","Railways: Huddersfield","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what plans he has to increase railway links from Huddersfield to other towns in the north of England.","false","Biography information for Mr Barry Sheerman","Huddersfield","Mr Barry Sheerman","9339"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758837","Department for Transport","false","2017-09-12","<p>Any rolling stock in operation between 2020 and 2022 will need to comply with the appropriate Accessibility Regulations. The public consultation for this franchise is ongoing and the response will inform the specification of the rolling stock. Future rolling stock strategy will be the responsibility of the successful bidder for the East Midlands franchise competition.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2017-09-12T07:58:18.757Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758837/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758837/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758837/answer",,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-09-07","Midland Main Railway Line: Rolling Stock","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what assessment he has made of the rolling stock which will be in operation on the Midland Mainline between 2020 and 2022 when the high speed trains are out of service and the new bi-mode trains will not yet be available.","false","Biography information for Andy McDonald","Middlesbrough","Andy McDonald","9580"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758838","Department for Transport","false","2017-09-12","<p>The rolling stock strategy for the East Midlands has been developed by reference to business case analysis of a range of rolling stock options including bi-modes, electric and diesel traction options. Rolling stock performance and cost are two of a range of parameters considered in this analysis. Ultimately the actual rolling stock solution for the East Midlands will be developed and implemented by the successful bidder in the current franchise competition.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2017-09-12T08:01:34.497Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758838/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758838/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758838/answer",,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-09-07","Rolling Stock","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what comparable assessment he has made of the performance and costs of bi-mode trains and electric rolling stock.","false","Biography information for Andy McDonald","Middlesbrough","Andy McDonald","9585"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758839","Department for Transport","false","2017-09-12","<p>The East Midlands franchise public consultation is ongoing and until feedback is received from the consultation, the final detailed timetable for rail services cannot be developed. The proposals for Midland Mainline rail services between Sheffield and London St Pancras are explained within the consultation document.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2017-09-12T15:31:00.877Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758839/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758839/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758839/answer",,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-09-07","Midland Main Railway Line","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what assessment he has made of the future pattern of rail services and timetabling between London and (a) Nottingham, (b) Leicester and (c) Sheffield as a result of the decision to introduce bi-mode trains on the Midland Mainline from 2022.","false","Biography information for Andy McDonald","Middlesbrough","Andy McDonald","9586"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758840","Department for Transport","false","2017-09-12","<p>Approximately £30m has been spent on preliminary works north of Kettering, including the raising of bridges on that part of the route. This will allow any future upgrade to be carried out with as little disruption as possible.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2017-09-12T07:53:43.363Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758840/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758840/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758840/answer",,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-09-07","Midland Main Railway Line: Electrification","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what the cost has been to the public purse of plans to electrify the Midland Mainline north of Kettering to date.","false","Biography information for Andy McDonald","Middlesbrough","Andy McDonald","9578"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758841","Department for Transport","false","2017-09-12","<p>Network Rail is continuing to invest in the Midland Mainline in Control Period 5 and 6 with over £1bn of investment planned including electrification of the route from Bedford to Kettering and Corby and additional track capacity. The majority of the planned journey time savings will still be realised through the provision of an additional sixth long distance train path each hour, allowing the industry to make more efficient use of the infrastructure, as well as allowing higher capacity services to run. These capacity and connectivity improvements are expected to be the key driver of the economic impacts of the Midland Main Line programme.</p><p> </p><p>By also introducing the new fleet of bi-mode intercity trains from 2022, we are maximising the benefits of the largest upgrade of the Midland Main Line since it opened in 1870. Passengers will also see reduced journey times on long distance services from Nottingham and Sheffield by up to 20 minutes in the peak and an increase in capacity across the network.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2017-09-12T12:22:27.187Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758841/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758841/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758841/answer",,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-09-07","Midland Main Railway Line: Electrification","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what assessment his Department has made of the effect that the decision to cancel the electrification of the Midland Mainline will have on the economy of the East Midlands.","false","Biography information for Andy McDonald","Middlesbrough","Andy McDonald","9579"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758842","Department for Transport","false","2017-09-14","<p>In the last seven years we have electrified more than 50 route miles and many more route miles are in the process of being electrified. This is much more than the 10 miles electrified by Labour in 13 years.</p><p> </p><p>As my Rt Hon Friend the Secretary of State said on 20 July, however, technology is advancing quickly, and this means that we no longer need to electrify every line to achieve the same significant improvements to journeys.</p><p> </p><p>Details on the sections of railway line where electrification is no longer considered necessary are contained in my Rt Hon Friend’s statement of 20 July.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2017-09-14T14:29:56.263Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758842/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758842/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758842/answer",,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-09-07","Railways: Electrification","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, which planned rail electrification projects have been cancelled in each of the last 10 years.","false","Biography information for Chris Ruane","Vale of Clwyd","Chris Ruane","9530"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758843","Department for Transport","false","2017-09-14","<p>No time has been saved by the electrification alone. Some of the routes have had major route upgrades, including line speed improvements, which has benefitted diesel trains as well as electric ones.</p><p> </p><p>The core purpose of electrification is not normally for speed Examples of this are between London and Edinburgh, where diesel and electric trains are scheduled in the same journey time.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2017-09-14T10:15:00.16Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758843/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758843/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758843/answer",,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-09-07","Railways: Electrification","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what the average savings in travel time were from each rail electrification project in England and Wales in each of the last 10 years.","false","Biography information for Chris Ruane","Vale of Clwyd","Chris Ruane","9529"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758844","Wales Office","false","2017-09-14","<p>Since 2012, the Coastal Communities Fund in Wales has provided £12,262,000 for 57 projects in Wales to help create new jobs and promote economic development on the Welsh coast.</p><p>Descriptions and funding levels for each project are available on the BIG Lottery website:</p><p><a href="https://www.biglotteryfund.org.uk/ccf" target="_blank">https://www.biglotteryfund.org.uk/ccf</a></p><p> </p>","Vale of Glamorgan","Alun Cairns",,"2017-09-14T10:25:19.347Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758844/answer","Biography information for Alun Cairns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758844/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758844/answer",,,,,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2017-09-07","Coastal Communities Fund: Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, which projects in Wales have benefited from the coastal communities fund in each year for which data is available.","false","Biography information for Chris Ruane","Vale of Clwyd","Chris Ruane","9550"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758845","Wales Office","false","2017-09-14","<p>I have had a number of discussions with Cabinet colleagues, including on tidal lagoons. I remain supportive of a tidal lagoon at Swansea Bay, however it is essential that we fully assess the costs and benefits of the project to ensure it represents value for money.</p>","Vale of Glamorgan","Alun Cairns",,"2017-09-14T10:26:48.397Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758845/answer","Biography information for Alun Cairns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758845/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758845/answer",,,,,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2017-09-07","Tidal Power: Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, what recent meetings he has had with Cabinet colleagues on tidal lagoons.","false","Biography information for Chris Ruane","Vale of Clwyd","Chris Ruane","9572"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758846","Wales Office","false","2017-09-14","<p>The table below show the proportion of Welsh exports and imports that were traded with the EU between 2014 and 2016.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Year</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Percentage of Welsh imports that come from EU countries</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Percentage of Welsh exports that go to EU countries</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2014</strong></p></td><td><p>42.9</p></td><td><p>64.3</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2015</strong></p></td><td><p>48.1</p></td><td><p>66.7</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2016</strong></p></td><td><p>48.6</p></td><td><p>67.1</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>Source: HMRC Regional Trade Statistics</p><p> </p><p>Data before this period is not available due to an improvement in methodology made by HMRC.</p><p> </p><p>HMRC do not receive information in respect of goods that move wholly within the UK. Goods partially created in Wales before being finalised by a separate company, in another region of the UK and exported are not included in the above figures.</p><p> </p>","Vale of Glamorgan","Alun Cairns",,"2017-09-14T14:35:53.783Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758846/answer","Biography information for Alun Cairns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758846/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758846/answer",,,,,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2017-09-07","UK Trade With EU: Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, what proportion of Welsh exports and imports were traded with the EU in each year for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Chris Ruane","Vale of Clwyd","Chris Ruane","9571"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758847","Wales Office","false","2017-09-14","<p>The distribution of EU structural funds in Wales is the responsibility of the Welsh Government. The UK Government does not hold these figures.</p>","Vale of Glamorgan","Alun Cairns",,"2017-09-14T10:27:55.747Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758847/answer","Biography information for Alun Cairns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758847/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758847/answer",,,,,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2017-09-07","EU Grants and Loans: Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, how much in EU structural funds has been spent in each local authority area of Wales in each year for which data are available.","false","Biography information for Chris Ruane","Vale of Clwyd","Chris Ruane","9531"
